ref_text: You knew me before the fame, don't lose me the more I change, no
tate_text:
Even though the fame is changing his persona, she, (the music), isn’t loosing him, as music is adaptable and it is still able to let Cole release his true feelings.

This line could also tie back with how he was talking about Tiffany, the first girl who died in his life. She knew him before he was famous, maybe her spirits still lives with him and he’s asking her not to lose him the more he changes in the world.

tate_text:
X has always seemed interested in benefiting the youth. In the outro of his official “Look At Me!” music video, he said:

the youth is never inspired to take a stand to make a difference. So I will speak for them. The youth, that is, the ones full of innocence. The ones inspired by the things around them, to matter.

He also took to his Instagram page once and posted the following on his story:

I wanna live long enough to look back at he things I’ve done, and say I positively benefited the youth or the world in some way

In January 2018, he started a movement called “#THEHELPINGHANDCHALLENGE” where he encourages young people to help other people in need. He even donated PS4s and musical instruments to Foster Homes, and claimed to have donated $100,000 to domestic violence programs.

The album version of this song does not include this outro.

tate_text:
Beyoncé speaks to both her fresh sense of style and her confident approach to feminism.

She calls on the paparazzi to come check out her outfit.  She rocks it confidently, and it is so “fly” and so “fresh” that it needs to be appreciated.



At the same time, Beyoncé employs a play on words that may be in reference to her role as a female activist.  If a man’s fly is down, his pant zipper is unzipped and his junk may be showing.  An onlooker might get a fresh look of what is underneath.

Male genitalia is a symbol of power and dominance.  Following the theme of LEMONADE, Jay Z (and men in general) may be exercising dominance over Beyoncé too often – to the extent that she has had enough.  He needs to zip up his fly, thereby receding his male dominance and treat her with the respect she deserves.

Bipolar Kanye switches between addressing himself in the second person (‘you might think they wrote you off’) and the first (‘They going have to rope me off’) in these lines, and throughout ye.

When he uses the second person, he is speaking to his “sunken-place” self. Depressed Kanye worries he’s becoming irrelevant, but happy Kanye won’t let that happen.

This could also be a reference to the common practice of doctors and clinics over-prescribing celebrities—sometimes resulting in the end of their career or life. “Write off” could be double entendre, as they’re writing the prescription as well as being responsible for the public dismissing (or “writing off”) the artist as troubled or insane.

19 Beloved, never avenge yourselves, but leave it to the wrath of God, for it is written, “Vengeance is mine, I will repay, says the Lord.”

Rather, he should be more focused on repaying this person with love and blessing, as commanded to in 1 Peter 3:9:

9 Do not repay evil for evil or reviling for reviling, but on the contrary, bless, for to this you were called, that you may obtain a blessing.

In an interview with No Jumper, Cole shared his thoughts about religion, particularly Christianity, and some of his experiences with faith throughout his life:

It hit a point where I had to question it for the first time. I felt bad about it. I felt guilty …for even having a negative thought about it. I went and got baptized, started reading The Bible, and I was scared as fuck. Then it hit a point in my life where I just fell off and said, “I’ll let the answer come.” As I got older, I felt like I got a personal understanding of what God is to me, a strong belief too.

This is not the first time Cole has talked about God in his music, talking about it in songs such as “Change.”

Producer Derek Watkins described how Ye got Kirk Franklin and the choir to fly in from Texas for this song.

How many people in the choir? We’ll keep that private, we’ll call that secret sauce. So we begin to have a conversation in the studio. Kirk’s in there with headphones and he said, “What are you hearing?” I told him that we wanted to amplify what was already there. He began to teach the choir the parts and he taught it in seven minutes, bro.

Franklin recorded his part over the weekend. When he flew back to put the finishing touches on the track on Monday, he was already receiving criticism from the Christian community for working with Kanye.

Franklin defended Ye, saying “I will not turn my back on my brother…to a lot of my Christian family, I’m sorry he’s not good enough, Christian enough, or running at your pace…and as I read some of your comments, neither am I. That won’t stop me from running. Pray we win.”

ref_text: [Produced by Kanye West and Che Pope with additional production from Eric Danchild, Noah Goldstein, No ID and Mike Dean]
tate_text:
“Bound 2” was a track that wasn’t initially a sample-based track. It was a band track with singing, no idea who. I got involved late in the game.

He came in one day and said he got inspired driving up the Pacific Coast Highway, on the way to my studio. He thought it would be a good thing to try the sample he found, so we tried that and the whole song changed. The chorus was still the old way, where it was sort of a band version. I took everything out of that and reduced it to one sort of ugly sounding synth. I would say the old version was more like MOR, R&B. That’s just an example of one song on Yeezus that changed a lot. Some of them changed a little, some of them changed a lot.

Always tryna send me off to rehab
 Drugs started feelin' like it's decaf
tate_text:
Abel has done so many drugs that they don’t numb him like they used to. The National Institute on Drug Abuse defines tolerance as “A state in which an organism no longer responds to a drug.”

Drug tolerance is broken up into four groups: dispositional (genetic), behavioral (ditto), pharmacokinetic (metabolic), and pharmacodynamic (repeated usage). Different drugs develop tolerance at different rates.

He's comin' home with his neck scratched, to catch flack
 Sweat jackets and dress slacks, mismatched
 On his breath's Jack, he's a sex addict
 And she just wants to exact revenge and get back
tate_text:
The smell of Jack Daniel’s whiskey in his breath, neck scratches, and mismatched clothing (likely because this man slept at another girl’s house and was in a hurry to leave), are visual indications that he cheated. “To catch flack” means to take criticism, so he knows that his girlfriend’s going to be mad at him for his infidelity.

During these lines, we can hear the fight between these two happening as glass shatters and a woman yells in the background.

He feels as if he is trying desperately to say no to this, and crumbling under Maria’s coercion, but to the consumers of the media, namely The Reynolds Pamphlet, he could have easily said no to this.  They are urging him to do so; his protests of “There is nowhere I can go” are still met with a resounding “Go! Go! Go!”

tate_text:
Em uses a simile comparing the depth of his emotions to the depth of oceans.

And if you ever wondered exactly how deep the ocean is, the bottom of the ocean is 6.8 miles deep at its lowest known point.

ref_text: Somebody walked in with a pound of that Bay Area kush
tate_text:
Kendrick alludes to the San Francisco Bay Area, but may also have the Emerald Triangle in mind (a triumvirate consisting of Mendocino, Humboldt and Trinity county). This region lies just north of San Francisco County in Northern California—both areas are renowned for their liberal majority and significant cannabis culture, stemming from the 1960s counterculture movement.



Kush (or OG Kush) refers to a cannabis indica strain popular among rappers, especially those from the West Coast. A pound of marijuana is the equivalent of about 450 grams and would typically be purchased with the intent of selling for a profit.

ref_text: There are so many to deflower!
tate_text:
We all know what Burr has on his mind…



In 1860, an anonymous author actually published a sexually explicit biography of Aaron Burr—The Amorous Adventures of Aaron Burr. The book, though undoubtedly highly fictionalized, details a number of his alleged sexual conquests.

This would be fine if Burr, like Drake, lived in the modern world, where he would be free to please as many ladies as would have him. However, by 18th century standards, there’s a bit more going on here.

When Burr is talking about deflowering, he’s literally talking about taking away a woman’s virginity. While pre-marital sex was not exactly verboten in the 18th century—about one-third of colonial brides were pregnant on their wedding days—a lady was expected to marry the man who got her in the family way. If a woman’s chastity was lost, whether it was through a consensual act or rape, her reputation could be ruined.

As women weren’t easily able to retain property or businesses, most had to rely on their husbands or, more tentatively, their fathers and brothers to provide for her income. Thus, if a young woman lost her reputation and became unable make an advantageous marriage, her whole livelihood could be threatened. The higher the class, the more important it was that a woman’s chastity was preserved, as such a girl would not have been brought up to make any contingency plans for her future.

Basically, Burr and his crew can joke all they want, but for women, the act of courtship was a deadly serious business.

Ariana compares herself to a plant, constantly growing. Like a plant, she needs to grow in the right area – mud provides soft soil and nutrients for plants to grow.

Ariana is realising here that she should lean into the pain and keep strong against it. Instead of shying away from everything that happened, Ariana stayed strong and went back to Manchester after the bombing for her One Love Manchester benefit concert, despite the possible danger she could have been in.

(Come on!) Sing with me (Sing!), sing for the year (Sing it!)
 Sing for the laughter and sing for the tear (Come on!)
 Sing it with me, it's just for today
 Maybe tomorrow the good Lord will take you away
tate_text:
In a song that deals with the impact of music on the listeners, this chorus, sampled directly from Aerosmith’s iconic 1973 power ballad “Dream On”, deals with its impact on the artists.

Life is short, so even artists like Eminem that are reluctant to embrace their impact on listeners eventually feel the need to “sing for the moment” and create music with real meaning while you still have the chance. Em later turned this concept into an Academy Award-winning single with “Lose Yourself”.

Fuck can I say? If life was a highway
 And deceit was an enclave, I'd be swerving in five lanes
 Speeds at a high rate, like I'm slidin' on ice, maybe
tate_text:
“Life is a Highway” is a song by Tom Cochrane, which has a similar leitmotif:

Life’s like a road that you travel on
When there’s one day here and the next day gone
Sometimes you bend, sometimes you stand
Sometimes you turn your back to the wind

Here, Eminem uses this metaphor to convey the chaos in his life. In terms of wordplay, “deceit” sounds like “this seat.” The meaning of “enclave” also functions well here, as “the seat was an enclave” could refer to the seat of a Buick Enclave.

ref_text: Please don't hit my phone if it ain't 'bout no commas
tate_text:
To “hit someone up” is a common slang phrase for contacting a person. J. Cole uses a similar phrase here, saying not to “hit” his phone, meaning he doesn’t want anyone to text or call him unless it’s about “commas.” This refers to large amounts of money, because a numerical amount in standard English is required to be marked with commas that separate hundreds, thousands, millions, and so forth.



Therefore, larger amounts of money will have more commas in them.
This line plays off the last line, where Jermaine talks about doubling his money and items.

J. Cole’s net worth at the time of the song’s release was estimated to be a little higher than $15 million.

ref_text: Cause I'm such a dreamer, a believer in a sense
tate_text:
These two lines bring to mind an old song from 1967, “Daydream Believer” by The Monkees.

Cheer up, sleepy Jean.
Oh, what can it mean.
To a daydream believer
And a homecoming queen.

A popular interpretation of the song is events after the marriage of a daydream believer and a homecoming queen. Their relationship is unconventional due to different social statuses, but their love gets them through hard times. Sampha could be referring to a relationship with a woman, or a “relationship” with the industry and one’s career.

Another point of reference might be The Dreamer/The Believer, the 2011 album by Common. Interesting that Sampha would drop the reference on Drake’s track, considering the beef war between Com and Drizzy.

ref_text: [Produced by Kanye West, Mike Dean & Plain Pat]
tate_text:
The song begins with an ominous, distorted vocal roar, sung by Justin Vernon of Bon Iver, with Vernon declaring:

I shoot the lights out

Which sets up the dark atmosphere of the track. The intro of the song is followed by a brief verse given by Ross, delivered in the rapping style of boom bap with his deep voice complementing the beat. The song ends in a spooky, hoarse vocal riff delivered by Vernon, reminiscent of the track “Thriller”. An extended catchy vocal riff, closes the track.

The song heavily features bombastic tribal drums, and paranoia-inducing strings that create a feeling of tension. The beat of “Monster” has been described as a “hyperventilating death rattle”, the song was permeated with dark, urgent-sounding moans.



This monstrous beat has been reused for a freestyle by Kendrick Lamar, another by Nitty Scott and has been sampled numerous times. Interesting to note is that it’s one of the few beats, by Kanye standards, without a sample.

tate_text:
In the interview below with Cole explains that he had some pretty dark thoughts while writing this album, and even suffered from depression from the pressure he faced.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kSzPG0xMpLM&feature=youtu.be

He’s worried that Born Sinner will flop and maybe end his career.

He’s suggesting that part of the reason he’s worried is because he’s letting the Devil in him work, instead of trusting God.

On his Truly Yours 2 EP, Cole hints at the possibility of his album flopping with this line:

But I finally put my Momma in that E class, nigga
And I told her quit her job, but hold your horses
If my next album flops it’s back to the post office, both of us, shit
They’re saying that’s a real possibility
The thought alone is killing me

These lines are also a great play off the previous verse, where he’s asking the devil for his soul back. In these lines he blames the devil for nearly derailing his career, as he said it was on track until he let the devil lead the way.

Now he HAS his soul, and he’s not letting it go ever again for anything.

tate_text:
The character is making a new religion to worship this girl as she is poetry in motion, graceful and beautiful. The fruit tree in many religions and cultures is representative of fertility and physical nourishment, most famously used in the story of Adam and Eve and the tree of life (an apple tree). Instead of an apple, Kendrick uses the pear tree, perhaps alluding to the feminine form.

He is blindly obsessed with this deceitful woman (Mona Lisa). The musical arrangement in the background of this section portrays the feeling of euphoric love for this woman that the character has.

Last night I had a bad dream
 That I was trapped in this city
 Then I asked is that really such a bad thing?
tate_text:
Cole is saying that he had a dream that he was trapped in the city, but he can’t seem to determine whether it’s a good or bad thing.

The reason why he says this is because in his town they rob people on a daily, even for the smallest things, like a watch. So if he were to actually become something and gain riches he would be a target for being robbed and gunned down for his possessions.

Cole also stated at a University that in Born Sinner he talked about his struggle with leaving his town to go to a big city. He said it was scary but he had to take the risk and move out there “with a dollar and a dream” and make something out of himself. Otherwise he would’ve stayed home and never prospered.

ref_text: O.J. like, "I'm not black, I'm O.J." …okay
tate_text:
While on trial, O.J. Simpson supposedly uttered the quote “I’m not black, I’m O.J.” Though there’s no substantial evidence, friends and acquaintances back up the theory, and it has been used in media retelling the story since—the earliest being the 2002 documentary O.J.: A Study in Black and White. It also appeared in the 2016 documentary O.J.: Made in America as well as FX’s The People v. O.J. Simpson:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xvDMetl7mKU

JAY-Z spoke on this subject in the footnotes special for this song, noting the need for those with visibility to not cast aside their background as a scapegoat:

We tend to, as black people—‘cause we never had anything, which is understandable—we get to a place and we just think we separate ourself from the culture. You know, like where O.J. will get to a space where he’s like, “I’m not black, I’m O.J.” … It’s gonna take for the way-showers to do it and then not get to that point and then turn into like, “I ain’t black, I’m O.J.”

Other sources indicate O.J. may have said the quote during a boycott of the 1968 Olympics, when he was “reportedly pressured by his friend to ‘take a stand’ along with other black Olympic athletes.”

tate_text:
Here, Jay pokes fun at the negative comments made online about his looks — for example, the Joe Camel look-alike meme. In relationships, looks are known to sometimes be cast to the wayside when money comes into the picture, so he points out the fact that to those people, it should be irrelevant with his almost-billionaire status.

The last two lines also contain wordplay on appearances – “Pretty much” and “handsome checks.”

This isn’t the first time Hov has used these appearance verbs in his rhymes. This, from 2008’s “Jockin' Jay-Z (Dopeboy Fresh)”:

I ain’t no pretty boy, I got a gorgeous wrist
Cut handsome checks and my flow’s pretty, sick

Knowin' that no matter what bars I come with
 You're gonna harp, gripe, and
 That's a hard Vicodin to swallow,
tate_text:
Eminem knows no matter what new music he puts out, he will face criticism from fans and the media. He plays off the idiom “a hard pill to swallow,” which refers to something that’s difficult to accept; Vicodin is an opioid pain medication that has high risk for addiction and dependence.



The topic of drugs has always been well explored in Eminem’s music. He has a history with pill addiction that almost killed him, a story he recounts towards the end of Revival.

What becomes evident here is that Eminem fears negative review, describing it as hard to accept. This is adding to the line in this song presented image of him: He is not perfect, and he has self-doubts.

tate_text:
A kingpin is a person at the top of some game; it could be referring to rap or crime, but the term most often refers to the drug trade. Presumably in comparison to a weighing scale, James can make the trap tilt (or “lean”) now that he has his weight up.

Cole describes the coke supply, which is high in both quality and quantity. The quality is great enough to make a fiend’s high feel heavenly. Meanwhile, the quality of the drug is so great that users figuratively grow wings, referencing an OD and obtaining angel wings from death.

Cole also uses wordplay with the words “lean” and “crack,” both of which are drugs. The imagery Cole paints in these lines are reminiscent to the 2002 film, Paid In Full. In the movie, three men become drug dealers and eventually gain all of the cocaine in Harlem. Not to mention that the movie includes a Scarface scene, which is also referenced in this verse.

tate_text:
Cole always appreciates the love and support that his fans give him every time he drops some music but he reminds them that he is a human being, not a God. He urges them to keep faith in themselves.

At the end of his song “Roll Call” on the second installment of his Every Given Sunday series, he reminisces on a conversation with a fan and reminds him of this:

And the young boy from a show down in Hampton
Told me that my song was the reason he beat cancer
Ain’t know what to say, I just froze
Little too deep, I suppose..
But after a year of review, I figured out it wasn’t me, it was you nigga
Congratulations.."

ref_text: Look at the cards that we've been dealt
tate_text:
Ariana compares her tumbling relationship to a game of poker, stating that they have to deal with what life has given them.

This line is similar to lyrics from her 2014 track “Best Mistake” featuring Big Sean, where she says:

Dealing with emotions that never left
Playing with the hand that we were dealt in this game

This line also shares similarities with lyrics from the title track of her August 2018 album, Sweetener:

When life deals us cards
Make everything taste like it is salt
Then you come through like the sweetener you are
To bring the bitter taste to a halt

ref_text:
And when I'm over only pray
 That I flow from the bottom
 Closer to the top
 The higher that I climb
 The harder I'mma drop
tate_text:
The higher Abel gets on his drugs, the harder he will crash on his come down.

These lines also touch on his imminent climb in the music industry. Many artists sell out and “drop” lower quality music the more famous they become, eventually leading to the demise of their careers. However, The Weeknd has never been afraid of this commonality. He has touched on this topic in “Rolling Stone”, “The Fall”, and even in an open letter to his fans.

He has also acknowledged:

I’m not really scared of failing, because I already know what it means to be on the ground.

tate_text:
Abel is addressing his older fans in this verse. He questions why they had to share his music with other people like a girl would do when she talks to her friends about their sexual encounter and how good it was.

Now that the word has spread about how amazing his music is, plus how amazing he is in sex, his phone is blowing up because of this unwanted attention, leading him to change his phone number constantly. He tells them that they could’ve kept him all to themselves but now they have to share him with the entire world which might make them lose the interest they had in him.

However, Abel foreshadowed this situation back in “Rolling Stone”:

So baby love me
Before they all love me
Until you won’t love me
Because they’ll all love me

The question based style is reminiscent of 50 Cent’s “21 Questions”:

Drake heard Cole’s original version of this song and fell in love with it. Whilst discussing their upcoming tour together, Drake found out Cole was intending to re-do it for Friday Night Lights. Drake proceeded to tell Cole: “Save me a 16”.

ref_text: Forget about me (Ari-Chan)
tate_text:
Chan (ちゃん) is a Japanese san (honorific suffix) used to describe a child, close family member, or lover, and is used as a term of endearment. Ariana Grande shows appreciation for the Japanese culture by including this ad-lib, alongside using it on the cover art for December 2018’s “imagine”,“ and in the music video for January 2019’s “7 rings.”

アリちゃん (Ari-Chan) has been learning Japanese since 2015. She’s very fond of Japanese culture and wants to connect more with her fans. Additionally, in January 2019, she had to get a tattoo covered since it was supposed to say “7 rings” in Japanese, but instead it said “small charcoal grill.” Ayumi Furiya, her tutor, stood up for her in an interview with The Cut:

For “seven rings”, you’re supposed to have three kanji characters but she only got two, which makes sense because tattoos are painful. With three kanji characters, sometimes you can drop one character, but unfortunately, she had to have the middle character.

More recently, while J. Cole and Kendrick Lamar were touring as supporting act for Eminem’s Rapture tour, the duo got interviewed by an Austrailian radio show The Bump Show. When asked about this collabo, Kendrick goes into further depth:

I was in Detroit. He brought me out to Detroit… So, he brought me to the studio. Told me to come to the studio to do the hook. So I go in and do the hook and he’s like ‘I like the hook.’ Boom, right? He gives your space. I took as him kicking everybody out to see if that’s really you writing them raps. That shit writing. When I’m the booth, and he’s walking in, then all done with the verse, I mean actually rapping it. He runs out like he don’t want to hear it. [J. Cole: Like he don’t want to to hear it. Yo, he’s a purist dawg! Rap purist. Yeah, it’s like a respect.]

ref_text:
I'll pass the weed to the pastor
 We all are sinners, won't you send us to bible study faster?
 Your hypocritesque reaction a blasphemy,
tate_text:
This line suggests that Kendrick knows the truth behind society’s lies. For example, the belief that all pastors are all around pure saints just because they’re religious is false. He knows that they too dabble in “sins” such as smoking weed.

Therefore, them pretending to be surprised at such a lyric would be considered “blasphemous” and quite hypocritical since religion teaches that people should be honest and forthcoming of their sins.

(Fun fact though: The Christian bible actually never directly states that smoking is a sin. It can be heavily implied, but it’s technically not stated.)



This line also connects to track 13 titled “Kush & Corinthians”—“Kush” being another term for weed and “Corinthians” being a chapter in the Christian bible. In the song, Kendrick discusses his moral conflicts within himself.

Ab-Soul, a frequent collaborator and friend of Kendrick, is also referred to as “The Pastor” and/or “Black Pastor,” as well as a large consumer of Marijuana.

 I see you nigga, this ain't no Rolex, it's a AP nigga
 I'm hot, dog, catch up to me nigga—uh, couldn't resist
tate_text:
I’m hot, dog, catch up with me nigga.

Hot dawg = Catch up or Hotdog = Ketchup

Cole’s clearly playing with words here. First, he means that he’s a top dawg, try to be on his level or try to catch up. Second, he’s implying that he’s literally a hotdog. What goes well with hotdogs? Ketchup, yes.

Finally, the phrase “Couldn’t resist,” takes the conclusion that Cole couldn’t resist inserting/making puns, silly puns. Plainly, this shows Cole being funny.

Bitch, don't kill my vibe!
 You ain't heard the Coast like this in a long time
tate_text:
The period from the mid 80’s to the mid 90’s is often called Hip Hop’s Golden Age. Dr. Dre, Tupac, Snoop Dogg were all actively turning out great albums in this era. It was also the time in which there was a feud between artists and fans of the East Coast hip hop and West Coast hip hop.

Starting at the end of the 90’s, there was a lot of criticism from both critics and fans about the state of hip hop. Eventually Nas even called his 2006 album Hip Hop Is Dead.

However, Kendrick (and apparently many others) believe his music harkens back to an earlier era in hip-hop. Kendrick, from the West Coast, is here to bring the 90’s West Coast back.

ref_text: My pen's better, you don't write, trendsetter, you clone-like
tate_text:
I was on a Wayne kick then—there was speculation of ghostwriting. That’s where I was at with this line.

That type of accusation and that type of issue or proof would have put you out the game in the golden years of hip-hop.

I am noticing that people don’t care and I am noticing that – not even as fans, but as like journalists and hip-hop authoritarians. I watched them not give a damn and just give passes to all of that. So it’s just what the times call for. I am not going to be the writing police for anybody.

ref_text:
Yeah, it feels so good to be so young
 And have this fun and be successful
 I'm so successful, yeah
tate_text:
In 2008, a 15-year-old Ariana started her career, starring in the Broadway show 13. Two years later, she was cast as Cat Valentine in Nickelodeon’s Victorious, and starred in a spinoff until 2014.

Ariana was 25 when she released Sweetener, and by then, she had already racked up a net worth of $45 million. Sweetener’s lead single, “no tears left to cry,” even broke a U.S. Billboard record, making her the first artist in history to have the lead singles of four albums debut in the top ten.

ref_text: If he can move through the rumors, he can drive off of fumes 'cause
tate_text:
In this metaphor, Kanye is ‘driving’ his career forward, through the rumors. Driving creates pollution, or ‘fumes’ – its creating a negative energy around him, from haters and his own paranoia and self analysis

However, he can ‘drive off the fumes’ i.e. continue moving forward off the negative energy by using it as ‘fuel’ for his music. Graduation is far more introspective and self centered than its predecessors.

Driving off fumes is another also another way of saying running on empty, showing how tired he is from all the work he’s doing.

This is a continuation form the previous line where he says “he don’t even stop to get gas”. He doesn’t want to jinx his success by getting gassed up from all that he has accomplished.

This keeps in track with the routine theme for ‘Ye. His arrogance is able to power him (“steam to power my dreams”) – despite haters, rumors, or having no actual fuel.

tate_text:
Kendrick pours detail into his encounter with the homeless man throughout the majority of the second verse, leading into a climactic final verse.



The homeless man’s empty stare pierces Kendrick. He becomes intrigued and doesn’t leave. As Kendrick becomes angry at the man, he articulates emotions of disrespect, anger, confusion – comparing his anger to throwing a baseball bat at the man’s throat.

This narrative paints a metaphor that calls to mind biblical parables, such as the story of Cain and Abel (“Am I my brother’s keeper?”) and
Matthew 25:45:

Truly I tell you, whatever you did not do for one of the least of these, you did not do for me.

“Like I was supposed to save him” can also be seen as foreshadowing the true identity of the man—the dramatic irony is excruciating.

 With you, with you, with you
 Exercise her right to work it out
 It's true, it's true, it's true
 Shout out to the birthday girls
 Say hey (Hey), say hey (Hey), (Ah, girl)
 Everyone deserves a night to play (Play)
 She plays, only when you tell her no
tate_text:
The woman in this song is the baby mama of the man who killed Kendrick’s friend, a story detailed in “Sing About Me.”  Kendrick makes this connection explicit in the third verse.

With her ex-love in  jail, she’s getting horny and wants to work out her “walls,” but wishes she could do so with her incarcerated lover.

“Shout out to the birthday girls” suggests the woman is at a party, ready to find a guy for a hookup.

The lyrics highlight her mixed emotions. She still loves her man and misses him, but she resents that he’s still trying to control the relationship from jail.

ref_text: And can't arrive at a compromise so it's Black Ops
tate_text:
This is a wordplay on the elite, covert missions the government doesn’t want you to know about (Black Operations) and the fact that black Americans are stuck at an impasse with the police force. Despite acknowledging that violence achieves very little for the social justice, Em (as a black male) ultimately feels that he is faced with no other choice, so they might as well arm up and go to war.



The phrase “Black Ops” entered the vernacular mostly due to the popularity of the Call of Duty: Black Ops video game series. Em’s track “Survival” premiered as a pre-order bonus for Call of Duty: Ghosts (2013).

ref_text:
Mayo and went from Hellmann's and being rail thin
 Filet-o-Fish, Scribble Jam, Rap Olympics '97 Freaknik
tate_text:
Hellmann’s is a brand of mayonnaise and McDonald’s Filet-o-Fish is a cheap sandwich. “Mayo” is also a derogatory term used to describe white people. In fact, Charlamagne Tha God, whom Eminem mentioned on “The Ringer,” often uses “mayonnaise” to describe white people he thinks are racists.

Eminem is talking about advancing in his career. He went from being a poor dad to attending big time hip-hop festivals like Scribble Jam and placing second in the ‘97 Rap Olympics. The Rap Olympics was the turning point in his career, as a demo tape handed out during this event ended up in the hands of Jimmy Iovine and Dr. Dre from Interscope Records:

https://youtu.be/DkALZe31QPQ

Freaknik was a large event held in Atlanta, Georgia, from 1983 to 1999, which consisted mostly of students from historically black universities.

Abel stresses that if you haven’t experienced trauma like this, it may not be possible to relate to her decision making. Despite the damage that prostituting herself causes, the vicious cycle she’s trapped in is hard to break.

Bey is playing with themes of power dynamics here; this line is representative of that major sexual motif on this eponymous and highly personal album. Telling her man to be the “boss”, to take control and use her as his stress relief while simultaneously repurposing the word “blow” for cunnilingus and confidently demanding her own cherry tearing release powerfully juxtaposes ideas of female dominance and submissiveness, challenging preconceived notions of feminism by choosing to not be the boss in this moment and yet easily remaining the one with the real power.

In love with the baddest girl in the city, I wish I knew her
I wish I won’t so shy, I wish I was a bit more fly

To “shoot one’s shot” is another phrase for asking someone out. Cole connects this to “brick”, a basketball term for a terribly shot ball that hits the backboard or the rim:



The narrator fails whenever he attempts to pursue someone, leading him to think he isn’t fit for romance. This insecurity contrasts with his friends' confidence in their “slick” flirting skills.

“I put my heart in a click” ties together the overall message of how social media has influenced finding love. Since he’s uncomfortable approaching this girl, the narrator expresses affection through liking (clicking) her photos.

tate_text:
While fighting with his girl, it seems that one of them said something they regretted. Kanye’s OK with it, though, since he believes giving your opinion (negative or positive) is better than saying nothing at all.

Kanye has expressed this sentiment before on “Bring Me Down”:

Everybody feel a way about K but at least y'all feel something

And Jay Z said something similar about Ye on The Breakfast Club:

That’s what great art is. It’s polarising… It force you to have an opinion, you know? At least you’re not like wishy washy about it.

ref_text:
I'll be around forever 'cause my skills is tip-top
 To any amateur niggas that wanna get rocked
tate_text:
Although trap music and “mumble rap” is currently considered mainstream music, J. Cole claims he won’t die out like he predicts most of the “mumble rap” scene would. He says his skills are “tip-top”, meaning a high part or point of excellence that leads up with perfection. Consequently, Cole believes that his musical influence will last forever.

This also isn’t the first time that Cole has challenged amateur rappers. On “Everybody Dies” he says:

The OG gatekeep rappers
The would-you-take-a-break-please rappers
Bunch of words and ain’t sayin' shit, I hate these rappers
Especially the amateur eight-week rappers

ref_text:
Me with no makeup, you in the bathtub
 Bubbles and bubbly, ooh
tate_text:
“Bubbles” occur in both bubbly, another name for champagne, and in bubble baths. In a December 2018 interview with Billboard, Ariana joked:

I am champagne. You know how people say we’re 60 percent water? I’m 60 percent pink Veuve Clicquot.”

In the same interview, Ariana also described her hit November 2018 single, “thank you, next”:

It’s me and my besties tipsy off champagne — and me with a broken heart — just letting it out and having fun."

Ariana toasts champagne whether it’s a difficult time or a celebration. In a December 2018 Pop Sugar interview, she gave the inspiration for the album that will succeed August 2018’s sweetner:

feminine energy and champagne and music and laughter and crying.

Interestingly, in 2010, three years before her career as a musician began to take off, she recorded a song titled “Pink Champagne,” but it did not make it onto her debut album Yours Truly, although she released the studio version in 2013 and performed it during The Honeymoon Tour in 2015.

ref_text:
And I’m never gonna stop until I make ‘em
 Drop and burn ‘em up and scatter their remains,
tate_text:
This couplet (the last “I’m” included) is the phrase in which Lafayette spits out 19 words in an approximately 3 second span, which makes it the fastest set of lyrics in Broadway history, according to FiveThirtyEight, as mentioned in the song’s description.

Daveed Diggs is a veteran of such mind-boggling pace, dealing out some seriously fast verses as an MC in clipping., his LA rap group.

According to LMM’s interview on Stephen Colbert, this line is also intended to show Lafayette’s evolution from a weak English speaker in his first appearance in the show to this point, where his command of English language is the most powerful of anyone in the show.

ref_text: [Produced by Nineteen85, Majid Jordan & Noah "40" Shebib]
tate_text:
This song started as a beat by Nineteen85. Then Majid—half of the OVO-signed duo Majid Jordan—laid some vocals over it while Jordan sped it up to infuse the track with more energy. They handed it over to 40 and Drake, and the rest is history. As 40 told the FADER:

Majid Jordan captures a moment that Drake and I have always been chasing.

This is a 100BPM song with a four-on-the-floor rhythm with a clap on every second beat for most of the track. The main arrangement is drums, synths, bass, vocals and backing vocals. It’s been described by SPIN as “synth-soaked R&B” meeting “slow-motion deep house”. The song uses a lot of reverb to give it a spacious feeling. During the final hook white noise cuts and hi-hats are added in to highlight the grand finalé.

Grammy nominated producer Chilly Gonzales broke down the keys used in the beat:

This gunshot ad-lib alludes back to the Chief Keef reference in verse 1. Keef made this ad-lib famous in his mixtape and song of the same name. This word has become a staple in many trap songs, as well as after shooting references by mainstream artists, such as Jay.

#OPINION #2
Not really, he’s alluding to himself shooting. People have used “Bang!”, making a gunshot noise, as an ad-lib before Chief Keef’s existence.
Listen to my nine millimeter go bang!
-KRS ONE

 'Cause he was an angel
tate_text:
Ariana and Mac Miller (Malcolm James McCormick) started dating in August 2016 and broke up in May 2018. Even after breaking up, they decided to stay friends.

Following Mac’s DUI charge in May 2018, a fan posted on Twitter, blaming Ariana for breaking his heart, to which she responded how her relationship with Mac was “toxic” and how his addictions were overwhelming for both of them.

Mac Miller died on September 7, 2018, from an accidental overdose of fentanyl and cocaine. Five days following his death, Ariana posted a tribute to Mac via Instagram, with the caption:

i adored you from the day i met you when i was nineteen and i always will. i can’t believe you aren’t here anymore. i really can’t wrap my head around it. we talked about this. so many times. i’m so mad, i’m so sad i don’t know what to do. you were my dearest friend. for so long. above anything else. i’m so sorry i couldn’t fix or take your pain away. i really wanted to. the kindest, sweetest soul with demons he never deserved. i hope you’re okay now. rest.

tate_text:
When I’m writing, I’m in the syllable game. I’m connecting 5-6-7-8 syllable phrases where every syllable rhymes. I get heavy into that. When I start rapping something, and I think of more syllables that connect with it, sometimes I want to just keep the scheme going forever.

I’ve done it before in songs, where the syllable scheme of the first verse ends up being the syllable scheme of the second verse, and the third verse — all the way down. I do it because the lines start connecting and making sense. Once I find something and lock in, it comes out pretty quick.

ref_text:
‘Cause I'm a renegade!
 Never been afraid to talk about anything
 (Anything?) Anything! (Anything)
tate_text:
He has no qualms rapping about anything, no matter how offensive society considers it.

Both Jay-Z and Eminem have made many songs that either challenged social order or drew criticism for being downright offensive.

Examples include:
-99 Problems
-Mosh
-3 a.m.
-Hard Knock Life (Ghetto Anthem)
-Kill You

The way Jay-Z questions “anything?” after Em says “anything”, is an allusion to Jay’s song Anything. The chorus sampled in Jay’s song sounds just like Em in Renegade.
http://youtu.be/odThhIA2gUM?t=1m26s

 This line may also echoes the refrain from Oliver Twist in which the Artful Dodger reconfirms he would do anything for love.

Jay Z and Eminem are like the Artful Dodger – they’re devoted and would do anything and say anything. Like Em and Jay, The Artful Dodger grew up on the streets and had to make his own way.

Check it out at 1:19 and 4:44 here:
https://youtu.be/ey0D53Dxl3M

Jay Z might also be familiar with the character and story seeing as in 2007 he bought the luxury clothing brand, Artful Dodger. It also wouldn’t be the first reference to musicals (see Hard Knock Life).

tate_text:
Kayla Duckworth, Kendrick’s sister, voices this line. She also appeared at the end of 2015’s “Black Friday.”

Kendrick uses this line to give his dad a shoutout. When he was a newborn baby on his way home from the hospital, his dad was blasting Big Daddy Kane in the car, and his mother asked him to turn it down. His dad refused and said the loud music is good for him. Kendrick is attributing his skills and success in the music industry to his early exposure.

ref_text: It was like winnin' a used mink
tate_text:
A mink is basically a high-class ferret, with fur used for luxury clothing and rugs.



A used mink is ‘bittersweet’, it’s a tainted prize–Em made it, but he sacrificed a lot to get there.

Rest assured that Eminem did in fact say “mink”: it says so in the digital booklet. It also fits the rhyme scheme: “mink,” “shrink,” “think.”

Four in the mornin', and I'm zonin'
 I think I'm possessed, it's an omen
tate_text:
See above

 The book “Skinhead” by Nick Knight (the video’s director) might be a good start. Skinhead has its roots in the British Mod subculture.The music that Mods listened to was primarily Jamaican Ska and Northern Soul (Motown). It was mostly being played by black DJ in London clubs. The skinhead look is a British working class interpretation of the Jamaican Rude Boy look. I think that Kanye is aware of this history. I think in a way he is calling for unity among the oppressed (aka poor) regardless of color.

tate_text:
To “gas” someone up is to fire them up, to pump them up, to convince them to act in a certain manner.

Jay explained that his own crew was gassing him up to go at Prodigy.

Notice the figurative similarity between the words “ass” and “clap.”

Everybody wanted it to happen, like they did! There was a time like everybody was like ‘please, please let this guy go away’

He re-ups on the final line from the first verse. This isn’t just rap music, this is Jay’s life and livelihood. He will kill you.

ref_text: [Verse 2: Nicki Minaj & (Beyoncé)]
tate_text:
In an interview with Hot 97, Nicki explained the advice Beyonce gave her before recording her verse:

She told me, ‘I want you to be you. I don’t want you to hold back.“ I said, 'You sure?’ She said, ‘Yeah. I want you to just be you and do you.’ I was actually in New York writing the verse. I recorded the verse in New York and she stopped by the studio. She was such a sweetheart. She was hyping me up, like, ‘Yeah, do your thing. Don’t hold back. Go in.’ And I said, ‘Okay, all right.’

Nicki also continued to describe her ties to Bey and her music in the past:

When I was putting out mix tapes and stuff, I would always remix her stuff. I have a dope remix that my fans have always been in love with, to one of her songs, “Sweet Dreams,” [that] me and Wayne did/ I figured that eventually we would do something together. I mean, I’m not gonna lie. Recently I thought it would never happen ‘cause I felt like if she was going to ask me, she would have been asked me. I think the stars aligned the right way. We are just in the right places in our careers that it makes sense now. I feel like, with the release to her last album, her records are geared to what I do now, and so it is what it is.

ref_text: [Produced by Dr. Dre]
tate_text:
“My Name Is” was the first song we recorded. We recorded three or four that day, in like six hours. One song was called “Ghost Stories” and one was “When Hell Freezes Over.” I feel like there was one more but I can’t remember what it was. We always have this discussion, because Dre says it’s four.

Paul used to live in New Jersey, right across from Manhattan. He had an apartment he shared with three roommates. I was over, sleeping on the couch. We didn’t have money yet, really. We had already filmed the video, and we saw it for the first time on MTV. It came on really late at night. I was sleeping on the couch when Paul saw it for the first time.

That’s when it was like, “Okay, this isn’t a joke anymore.” We had kind of felt that, being in the studio with Dre and shit. But once that single came out, my life changed like that. Within a day. Just going outside. I couldn’t go outside anymore. In a day. It went from the day before, doing whatever the fuck I wanted to do, because nobody knew who the fuck I was, to holy shit, people are fucking following us. It was crazy. That’s when shit just got really — it was a lot to deal with at once.

Right after the first single came out, I did a signing at the Virgin Megastore in Times Square. While I was there, I got served by a court processor. They knew where I’d be, and they had to physically serve me. The guy got tackled. He was stupid. You don’t need to physically serve someone anymore, like in the movies. But the guy was being a cowboy. It was some lawsuit from my mother, I think.

Young and we alive, whoo!
 We never gonna die, whoo!
tate_text:
Rappers often talk about wanting their legacy to live longer than they do. Legendary rappers like 2Pac and The Notorious B.I.G. have had their legacy live on—Yeezy wants to join the elite group.

 The idea of “dying twice” was popularized by Irvin D. Yalom (and later street artist Banksy):

I mean, they say you die twice.  One time when you stop breathing and second time, a bit later on, when somebody says your name for the last time

ref_text:
I told him, "Please don't die over the neighborhood
 That your mama rentin'
 Take your drug money and buy the neighborhood
 That's how you rinse it"
tate_text:
Street gangs are territorial and gang members put their lives on the line for property that’s ultimately government owned. JAY-Z experienced how violent a drug dealing lifestyle can be and rapped about it on his 1996 track “Dead Presidents”:

I had near brushes, not to mention three shots close range
Never touched me: divine intervention

Jay retired from the street life and encourages other drug dealers to do the same. There were even rumors he would buy his childhood home—Marcy Projects. On DJ Khaled’s 2016 song “I Got The Keys,” Jay commented on the importance of ownership:

‘Til you own your own you can’t be free

“Rinse it” is a play on laundering drug money, cleaning up the neighborhood, and also leasing the apartments for profit (“rents it”).

ref_text:
Unfollow fear and just say "You are blocked"
 (You can feel it, feel it, yuh)
 Just know there is so much room at the top
tate_text:
This clever lyric is not only an empowering reminder to banish fear, it also perfectly nods to the role of social media in her career.

She’s saying to “unfollow” fear and tell it that it’s been “blocked” as can be done on Twitter and Instagram. These are familiar and intuitive concepts for her fans, and somehow turns the dark, nebulous concept of fear into a manageable construct that can be willed away with the push of a button.

ref_text:
Me, I wasn't taught to share, but care
 In another life, I surely was there
 Me, I wasn't taught to share, but care
 I care, I care
tate_text:
These lyrics were actually written by Anna Wise while working with Steve Lacy. However, Kendrick reached out about using the lyrics.

Anna spoke about the collaboration during an interview with Complex in April of 2017, saying:

But for “Pride,” it’s really interesting because I didn’t even write that for him. I wrote that in a session with Steve Lacy where just him and I were together. Kendrick and I haven’t been able to meet up to work. I send him little, you know, voice memos. I’m always sending him little things just to be inspired by.

Additionally, Anna stated that she didn’t overthink these lyrics:

Often when I write, I allow the stream of consciousness to come and I sing whatever comes out. So I sang something, and then we listened back to it. Actually, what I sang when we did the demo is exactly what it is. We didn’t change anything.

The two have collaborated on many songs before, including: “Bitch, Don’t Kill My Vibe,” “Money Trees,” “Hood Politics,” and “​untitled 05 | 09.21.2014.”

https://twitter.com/annathewise/status/852687447674769408

It should be noted that, when the chorus is sung, both Steve Lacy and Kendrick space and drag out the lyrics to give it more effect.

Kendrick is using Anna’s lyrics here, which allude to the common saying that “sharing is caring” to relay that he cares about himself and others but cannot bring himself to share what he has, whether it’s his wealth, advice, personal history, or possibly his position in the music industry, all potentially to maintain his own happiness over flashiness.

The caring nature that Kendrick attributes to himself is likely exclusive to his God, family, friends, and fans, while his distaste for sharing may refer most plausibly to people he doesn’t particularly care for. With his own compassion in mind, Kendrick feels that if there had been a perfect world, he would have been apart of it in a different lifetime. Then, possibly considering the prideful nature of such a statement and/or reflecting on his distaste for sharing, he reevaluates and says, “Maybe I wasn’t there” in the refrain that follows, showing the humbleness that he fears that he may lose.

In another instance of apprehension to share, especially wealth (although Kendrick has engaged in philanthropy in the past), in his 2015 parable “How Much A Dollar Cost,” he refuses to give a homeless South African man a dollar because he is skeptical of the man’s intentions, and the man later reveals himself as God, leading Kendrick to repent and again, be humble.

ref_text:
These rappers insecure
 They talk about being a man so much
 I finally understand that they ain't even sure
 'Bout who they are and why they do this
 Guess I'm included in that category as a nigga who done had the glory
tate_text:
J. Cole may be referring to the success of his breakthrough single “Work Out” and the backlash he faced from his role model Nas.

In May 2010, J. Cole released “Who Dat,” which was supposed to be the lead single from his debut album Cole World : The Sideline Story. The song failed to achieve success in the charts, so Cole kept working on his debut album, trying to come up with better and catchier tunes. A year later, his label Roc Nation was finally satisfied with “Work Out,” a song that took a step back from J. Cole’s usual lyricism. It became the album’s lead single and J. Cole’s biggest hit single to date, and is arguably what turned him into a mainstream act.

This song may have brought J. Cole the “glory” and recognition from a wider audience, but his idol Nas expressed dislike for the song and disappointment in Cole’s abandon of lyricism.

Cole famously talked about this issue on “Let Nas Down”, from his sophomore effort Born Sinner.

ref_text: The Mercer legacy is secure
tate_text:
Hugh Mercer was a Scottish soldier and physician. He initially served with the Jacobite forces of Bonnie Prince Charlie, and with the British forces during the Seven Years' War (Known today as the French and Indian War), but later became a brigadier general in the Continental Army and a close friend to George Washington.

General Hugh Mercer was born in Scotland. At the age of 15 he attended the University of Aberdeen where he became a doctor.  He served as an assistant surgeon and army doctor for the army of Bonnie Prince Charlie in 1746 and 1747.

Mercer moved to Fredericksburg, Virginia where he again set up practice as a physician.  In this capacity, he treated members of George Washington’s family.  As his own family grew, Dr. Mercer arranged to purchase George Washington’s boyhood-home, Ferry Farm.

 Bottle full of pills, passed out on the curb
tate_text:
These lines are an interpolation of the lullaby “Hush Little Baby”.



Instead of trying to make someone fall asleep, X tells the narrative of suffering from depression. The silenced angel is either himself hiding his problems from the public eye, or an actual angel trying to stop him from being self-destructive. X’s story is a common one, with about twenty percent of people with mood disorders also being an addict.

tate_text:
For the outro Beyoncé channels Soulja Boy and borrows from his 2008 single “Turn My Swag On.”

The track was widely successful when it first dropped, selling over a million digital downloads, peaking at No. 3 on the Billboard rap charts and spawning freestyles from Fabolous, Jeezy, Gucci Mane, R. Kelly and Jadakiss; plus a remix with Lil Wayne. The song was also notably covered by the Hive-assumed rival Keri Hilson.

Here, Bey again asserts her flawless-ness confirming how powerful she is and how empowered she feels. This section also serves as a fitting precursor to the entire theme of the next song, “DON’T HURT YOURSELF.”

ref_text: ‘Cause it feels so empty without me
tate_text:
There’s two things Slim is bringing up (that haven’t been mentioned in earlier annotations)

After releasing The Slim Shady LP in 1999 and The Marshall Mathers LP in 2000 – both received by some with serious controversy over lyrical content – Eminem waited a full 2 years to release Without Me as the lead single in 2002.  During those 2 year there were really no musical controversies worth mentioning, and it is this Slim Shady is referring to, with a sly grin no doubt.

Furthermore, music had hit a real lull in 2001, the year without an Eminem album.  Not just for hip hop, but in general.  The top 5 selling albums in 2001 were an aging Michael Jackson, Shaggy, ‘N Sync, Enya(!?) and Staind(!?!?!!).  Not only was the music boring, the musicians really lacked any charisma, humour or distinct personality, the exact opposite for Marshall. When Eminem returned in 2002, he easily filled the void and took the number 1 spot for the entire year.

ref_text:
Always hated the boy, but now the boy is the man
 Mothafucka, I done grown up
tate_text:
Drake is likely talking about himself here. He’s often referred to himself as “The Boy” and he even does it in this album multiple times, including this song like he does here.

In “Furthest Thing”, he states

Yours truly, the boy

In “From Time”, Drizzy again states:

Who you settling for? Who better for you than the boy, huh?



He’s reiterating the issue in these bars: people always hated him for being himself, but now he doesn’t have to care because he’s undeniably running the game right now.

The story of your life here
 Two young stars was born and y’all gon’ die here
tate_text:
Cole was featured on “A Star Is Born” by Jay-Z. Kendrick incorporates himself in the idea as well, becoming the second young star. Kendrick also mimics whiny deliveries by emulating J. Cole’s style on his verse on the “TKO Remix”, which was a response to Kendrick’s “Control” verse.

Kendrick’s flow in the 3 lines starting with “story of your life..” is reminiscent of Drake’s on “Back to Back”. “Y'all gon die here” may or may not be a reference to Drake, but Kendrick has been known to throw subliminal jabs at Drake in the past.

ref_text: And I thought I was so smart
tate_text:
Burr considers himself to be a very smart man, and for good reason, but Theodosia is a revelation to him. The things he learned about the world and about himself, with the arrival of her birth, wouldn’t have been something he could have learned in books. He’s gained a new kind of knowledge and wisdom.

Whatever can be said of Burr’s pride and arrogance all fades out when he sees his daughter smile. Despite his flaws and shortcomings, his love for his daughter shows the audience that Burr is human and is relatable to modern day people.

Because everyone knows how the story ends (Burr kills Hamilton), Miranda struggled to sympathize the audience with Burr. “Dear Theodosia” is one of the key songs in Hamilton that helps the audience sympathize with the show’s antagonist.

ref_text: By providence, impoverished, in squalor
tate_text:
The word “providence” has a bit of a double meaning. Providence can mean provisions toward the future, i.e. the inheritance left to Hamilton by his parents and guardians. However, providence can also mean fate or God’s intervention in the world.

In the 18th century, ‘Providence’ was a popular way to refer to God, Himself. Thus, Hamilton grew up in a backwater of the Caribbean, impoverished and in squalor, because of both his lack of inheritance from his parents and the vagaries of fate/God.

Providence was also the name of another island colony  in the Caribbean sea established in the 17th century by British forces. Today it is known as Isla de Providencia or Old Providence Island.

ref_text:
See, I invented Kanye, it wasn't any Kanyes
 And now I look and look around and there's so many Kanyes
tate_text:
Kanye flexes his influence on music, fashion, and popular culture.

The vast majority of popular rappers today—Drake, Childish Gambino, Big Sean, J. Cole, Kendrick Lamar, Chance The Rapper, Tyler, The Creator, A$AP Rocky, Travis Scott—have all been influenced by Kanye one way or another. He also credits himself and Don C. with bringing back the Jordan Retro’s. In a 2013 interview with Sway Calloway, Kanye said:

The Jordans are only popular at this point because of two people — me and Don C. Because Don C was ordering them vintage Jordans when the IVs used to break apart at the sole. We were wearing them with the Louis Vuitton backpacks with the Polos. Brand Jordan looked at us and said, ‘Oh man, we’ve got to start retroing them.’

According to How Many of Me, there are only 1,610 “Kanye’s” in the United States and only one of them has the surname “West.” Were the other 1,609 named after the Kanye West?

ref_text:
I been movin' calm, don't start no trouble with me
 Tryna keep it peaceful is a struggle for me
tate_text:
Although Drake squashed his major beef​, he’s no stranger to conflict.

Most notably, he beefed with Philadelphia rapper Meek Mill in 2015 over claims that he didn’t write his own songs. Drake responded to these allegations with his diss tracks “Charged Up” and “Back to Back,” after which Meek Mill eventually responded with “Wanna Know.” After Drake’s OVO Fest, where he performed “Back to Back” and showed a slideshow of fan-made memes that dissed Meek Mill, Drake was widely considered the victor.

Drake rapped a similar bar during his verse on Lil Wayne’s “Family Feud”:

But this isn’t all about a callin' truce
I’m still dishin' out verbal abuse
That shit could get re-introduced
If somebody got somethin' they urgin' to prove, nigga

tate_text:
English playwright John Heywood used the phrase “Rome wasn’t built in a day” in 1538 to make the point that great things take time to build. The always-confident Kanye accepts this challenge, and gets to plotting out the next 503 year empire in the ruins of the past empire.



Kanye should be careful, though. While dark-skinned men and women have a natural SPF of roughly 13, as compared to 3-4 for Caucasians, this does not protect them from the sun entirely. Dark-skinned reggae icon Bob Marley died of skin cancer that was initially dismissed as a soccer injury because it wasn’t known that those of African descent could get melanoma.

tate_text:
This continues the idea that Kanye is losing himself due to this exploitation of his former soul mate. After he goes home from this encounter he will be just as soulless as he was before, because he’s throwing out meaning for temporary pleasure.

Note the clever wordplay here; soul mates without the soul are just mates. This implies a relationship based solely on “mating” (having sex), rather than based on love and emotion.

UK radio host Charlie Sloth also uses the “Perfect!”  sound bite. The sound is normally played during Fire In The Booth, a freestyle segment that has featured UK artists including but not limited to Giggs, Akala, and Chip.

Abel looks to the past for inspiration rather than his contemporaries. He bumps the Boston-based 1980s R&B group New Edition when he’s whipping his Bentley Mulsanne.

ref_text: Go Uptown, New York City, bitch
tate_text:
Uptown NYC is a very fashion-minded neighborhood with little tourism. Being a fashion connoisseur himself, Drake must spend a lot of time in the Uptown area.

There is also a large Hispanic population in Upper Manhattan, specifically in Washington Heights or the upper-western side of Manhattan, which ties in with the next line about Spanish girls loving him.



Also a reference to Drizzy’s song “Uptown” off of So Far Gone.

tate_text:
In March, 2016, Dreamville went to Austin, Texas to headline the seventh annual SXSW Takeover. Three days after the Sheltuh was raided by police, Jermaine was joined by Cozz, Bas, and Omen.

Although the team was away from home, engineer Juro “Mez” Davis, who is credited on the album, had just stepped out for lunch when he returned to see the SWAT team busting down the door.

tate_text:
Many drug addicts have been known to act irrationally when looking for money to buy drugs, doing things such as stealing other people’s items and selling those possessions alongside their own extremely cheap for a quick hit. An extremely desperate dope fiend could possibly even resort to murder if they feel that would get them what they want. Compton legend Eazy-E gave an example of actions from a desperate dope fiend:

He’s addicted, he’s a smoker but in Compton called a clucker
He used to have a house, car, and golden rings
But the cooky cooky crack took all those things
He must’ve been starving ‘cause he broke in my house
Caught the nigga on the street and straight took his ass out

Kendrick suggests he could either be in the presence of his drug dealing friends and encounter the desperate dope fiend or he could be just minding his business in a zone by himself and become a target of someone who might be foolish and strung out enough to try and rob a known gangster like Eazy-E.

ref_text: Alien brain, you Satanist (Yeah)
tate_text:
Eminem declared himself an alien on January 2018’s “Chloraseptic (Remix)”:

It’s ‘cause I’m an alien, that’s why I write 'til the page is outta space

He calls MGK a Satanist since he named his diss track, “Rap Devil.” The title of the diss track is a play on one of Em’s most popular hits, “Rap God.” The devil, or Satan, is considered to be the antithesis of God.

This line also connects with “In vain” in the previous line, a religious phrase found in The Ten Commandments:

Thou shalt not take the name of the LORD thy God in vain; for the LORD will not hold him guiltless that taketh his name in vain.

Drake’s girl questions his character, but he still lies to her. While in his eyes a white lie is better than revealing the truth, she might not feel the same way.

This dichotomy was explored on “Redemption,” where Drake raps:

Say to you
But 80 percent of it was the truth, yeah

ref_text: [Produced by Kanye West, Evian Christ, Dom Solo, Noah Goldstein, Arca and Mike Dean]
tate_text:
This is a very sexual song with what sound like porn samples, a simple sin/square bass, slowed drum samples and the same distorted one-shot from “Guilt Trip”. During the main section there’s even what sounds like a dog barking sample if you listen carefully. It begins at a very slow 43BPM and pushes up to 120BPM in the main section.

Kilhoffer, one of the album’s producers, said

“I’m in It” started out with a different sample and melody. Then Kanye removed the sample, and it lived as a six-minute arrangement for a while. Then Rick Rubin got ahold of it and structured it to flow as a three-minute piece.

Mike Dean said

[The song] had these crazy guitar parts and all this stadium stuff, and then Rick, Noah, and Kanye pulled it back. I wasn’t very happy with that at first, but it came out really well.

It samples “Lately” by Kenny Lattimore, at the part where he says “a dream”. The sample is pitched and slowed down. You can hear it at 0:33 in the original.

ref_text: If we don’t stop it we aid and abet it
tate_text:
On the surface, this lyric simply means “We have to stop Hamilton’s disastrous plan. If we don’t stop him, we’re helping him follow it through.” But, the words “aid and abet” signal to a deeper meaning.

In legal terms, to aid and abet is “To assist another in the commission of a crime by words or conduct,” and a misdemeanor. By using terms more commonly used in the courtroom, Burr, Madison, and Jefferson foreshadow what they’re about to do to Hamilton: charge him with embezzlement (a.k.a. stealing money from the US Government). Before they even say a word to Hamilton, our three Democratic Republicans planted the idea that the national banking system is just another elaborate scheme for Hamilton to syphon the people’s money into his own account.

ref_text:
Still you feel the need to go full tilt
 That Bruce Willis, that Blue Steel, that true skill
 When that wheel's loose, I won't lose will
tate_text:
In the previous lines, Eminem states that he has nothing left to prove, and he has already done it all, but “Still you feel the need to go full tilt”, confessing his drive to keep making more music.

Bruce Willis is most famously known for starring in Die Hard, n action thriller series, which can be described as “full tilt”. Eminem has mentioned Willis and referenced the saga in the song “Welcome 2 Hell” as he engineered this double entendre:

Bruce Willis on his death bed, last breath with an infection
Fighting it while he’s watching internet porn
About to meet his death with an erection
My God, what I mean is David Carradine jacking his penis
In front of his tripod choking his own neck, what part you don’t get?
I’m saying I’ll die hard

Blue Steel is a movie starring Jamie Lee Curtis, released in 1989. It is also labeled as a suspenseful thriller, and can be described as “full tilt”. Eminem has mentioned Curtis before in “No Favors” when he said;

They blame me for murdering Jamie Lee Curtis
Said I put her face in the furnace, beat her with a space heater
A piece of furniture, egg beater, thermos

After referencing his “true skill”, he adds, “When that wheel’s loose, I won’t lose will”, meaning that, even if he isn’t 100% (not all wheels are bolted on tightly), he wont lose will.  Em includes a play on words with “loose wheel” and “lose will”, reversing the order of words with similar pronunciation.

Finally, he ends a verse full of poker references (“ace in the hole”, “use the cards you’re dealt”, “stacked decks”) with a last one: Going “full tilt” in the professional world of poker is a term meaning to play aggressive and reckless right after losing a big hand.

ref_text: [Produced by DJ Toomp and Kanye West]
tate_text:
The song contains audio samples of ad-libs provided by Young Jeezy as well as background vocals provided by Connie Mitchell of the Australian electronic group Sneaky Sound System.  The drum track which uniquely uses the ride cymbal was laid down by DJ Troomp and upon first listen you know the driving crescendo of beats were made to be echoed loud and clear through an arena venue. In an interview, West further discusses the finer point of the song’s arena rock like qualities.

I hear records that are super hot for two months, but the records won’t last in people’s minds. I set out not to just make records that could hop off the radio instantly, but stuff that will speak to people. People still bring up ‘Spaceships’ to me. And people compare ‘Can’t Tell Me Nothing’ to ‘Spaceships’ saying that’s a song that inspires them when they going to work. But the chords itself, is like a Led Zeppelin rock melody. Yeah, you thinking it’s made for the car and you thinking it’s made for the club, and it works in the arena because DJ Toomp did the drums and all that, but the actual melody is made to rock 50,000 people.

This is a complex line not only because it deals with love, but also deception (disguise).

1) He could be saying that he’s full of love even though it may be shrouded or hidden by another emotion (hate?).

2) Also, he could say that LOVE itself is the emotion on the surface and underneath the disguise is hatred or ulterior motives.

Out in Hollywood bringin' back five or six hoes
 Fuck 'em then we kick 'em to the do'
 Nigga, you know how it go
 She deserved that, she a bird, it's a bird trap
tate_text:
It’s easy for Cole and his friends to bring a whole group of women back to the crib for quick one night stands.

But Cole doesn’t feel bad about using them. In fact, he thinks they deserve that kind of treatment because they’re “birds.”

Unlike the British slang “bird” (which is used as a neutral or complementary term for a woman), the word in this context describes a woman who’s stupid and promiscuous. The American “bird” evolved from the similar slang terms “chickenhead” and “pigeon.”



Cole believes these “birds” know what they’re getting themselves into, but partying with rappers is a “bird trap” that they can’t resist.

tate_text:
Kanye’s verse, rather than being about cementing his place at the top, is about how it feels to be there, and the good and the bad about it (something he was pondering a lot around the time of this song’s release – hence 808s and Heartbreak).

To help paint the medium for his lyrics, he lets the beat switch out for a bit to a more laid-back, melodic soundscape for the first part of his verse.



On a leaked tape:

I’m pushing the envelope! I wrote my fuckin' ‘Run This Town’ verse for a fuckin' month! When I heard Eminem’s verse on the Drake shit, I went back and rewrote my shit for two days. I canceled appointments to rewrite! I fuckin' care!

ref_text: You never learned to take your time!
tate_text:
This line references Chernow’s biography. Remember Hugh Knox, the preacher that took Hamilton under his wing in St. Croix?

An avuncular man with a droll wit, Knox worried that Hamilton was too driven and prone to overwork, too eager to compensate for lost time—a failing, if it was one, that he never outgrew. In later years, Knox [remembered to] Hamilton that he had been “rather delicate & frail,” with an “ambition to excel,” and had tended to “strain every nerve" to be the very best at what he was doing.

Hamilton’s tendency to overwork and write like he’s running out of time will follow him throughout his life, and this musical, intensifying with each loss; we already saw this happen after he lost his mother earlier in the song, and we’ll see it again in “Non-Stop” after losing Laurens.

There’s a striking musical emphasis here, foreshadowing the company refrain of “Time” that will become so important in the show’s final song.

In the original version of this song from “The Hamilton Mixtape,” the line was instead ‘you always had to speak your mind.’ It’s likely the line was changed to anticipate the theme of Hamilton “running out of of time” which emerged in later songs.

I'm a black king, black jeans on my black queen
 And her ass fat, too fat for a flat screen
tate_text:
This is a reference to cultural bias that ignores how most Kings in the Middle East and Africa (like the great Pharaohs of Egypt) had black skin.

This cultural bias extends to the entertainment industry too, where racism and colourism obstructs his “black queen” from following her dreams of stardom on screen. He knows she would struggle to pick up decent roles due to her shapely figure and darker skin.

 Lick a gun barrel, bitch, get off me!
tate_text:
Eminem labels Machine Gun Kelly as his son in the opening bars of the song, and he continues this metaphor by calling MGK his “offspring.”

These lines correspond with other MGK disses from Kamikaze, specifically on the song “Not Alike”:

I respond rarely, but this time Shady ‘bout to sound off
Like a fuckin’ cocked semi-GLOCK, demi-god
Let me put a fuckin' silencer on this little non-threatening blond fairy cornball takin' shots at me

Em is aware that he is giving MGK undeserved attention. Telling someone to “lick a gun barrel” or “eat a gun” is another way of telling them to commit suicide.

 To know some, if we both honest
 Who lasts? Yeah, you lie
tate_text:
Y’all might be thinking right now, I wonder, did he smoke something before he came up here? The answer is yes, I rolled up a little something, I knocked the edge off.

Ye is going to roll up a little something to get his mind right and knock his edge off so he can say what he really means.

It is time that Kanye be real with his audience and not dodge around this girl anymore. He can tell that she is not complacent with her position. When she says that she is better off without him, Ye knows that she is quite simply lying and that she knows she’s not doing well.

Mike Dean has expressed to Complex, when asked about The Life of Pablo (formerly known as SWISH), that Kanye doesn’t smoke very often. This high then added to the swagger and confidence of Kanye whilst he sings his thoughts.

I coulda bought a place in DUMBO before it was DUMBO
 For like 2 million
 That same building today is worth 25 million
 Guess how I'm feelin'? Dumbo
tate_text:
DUMBO is a neighborhood of Brooklyn, New York—the name is an acronym for “Down Under the Manhattan Bridge Overpass.” Brooklyn’s gentrification makes cheap property more valuable.

Dumbo is also a naive Walt Disney cartoon elephant with big ears that enable him to fly. Jay Z feels dumb, because he didn’t capitalize on real estate opportunities in Brooklyn when he had the chance.

ref_text:
La-di-da-da-a, da-a (I like this flavor)
 La-da-da-da-di-da-da-a, la-a (la-a, la-a, la-a)
tate_text:
This portion comes from “Give Me My Love” by Johnny “Guitar” Watson, from his 1977 album Funk Beyond the Call of Duty.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JW_Ks4yseHo

Watson was a blues and soul musician for decades, but saw his peak of success during the funk era.

“La di da” is a nonsense phrase with a long history. It started in 19th-century Britain, as a mockery of high-class speech, but by the time Watson used it, it was also used to show a carefree attitude.

Slick Rick and Doug E. Fresh would later immortalize the phrase in a partying context, in their 1984 hit “La Di Da Di,” one of the most-sampled songs in music history.

ref_text: The spot gets smaller and I get bigger
tate_text:
Like the previous line, Wayne is painting an image showing that the harder he works, the more work he has.

More specifically, the bigger he gets, as an artist, the less people can relate to him, and the less places he can fit in.



The literal belief that things around you are small, or are becoming smaller, is called micropsia, and can be the result of insomnia, hallucinogenic drug use, or psychological trauma.

ref_text:
Twinkletoes, you're breakin' my heart
 You can't fuck with me; go play somewhere, I'm busy
tate_text:
This is another diss/jab at Mobb Deep member Prodigy. Calling him twinkle toes is a reference to Prodigy’s early dance career, which Jay earlier used in this same song as a diss by calling him a ballerina.



To dance or do ballet you typically have to be light on your feet, i.e. twinkle toes .

This also further plays up on Prodigy’s lack of height as twinkle, (Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star is a kids story and song) is often a word associated with children. Small stature like (Prodigy’s) is often associated with little children.

ref_text:
I got a test for you
 You say you want my heart
 Well, baby, you can have it all
 There's just something that I need from you
 Is to meet my boys
tate_text:
Derived from the outro of “XO/The Host”, these lyrics summarize the meaning of “the Initiation.”

Abel is indoctrinating a girl into his lifestyle, which is a constant juggling of sex and drugs. She loves him, but ironically, he doesn’t really have a heart to provide her. What he does have, however, is a big crew, a crew that his girl must meet if she wants to be anything to Abel.

The implications of these lines embody the entire interpretation of the track:


His girl may have to meet and get approval from the entire XO group, which may include getting fucked by them all. Abel’s made it clear that he doesn’t mind sharing on several occasions. Nothing is a commitment for him.
The “boys” could also metaphorically refer to Abel’s assortment of drugs. This implies that the only real friends he has are drugs, and they’re the only entity that can get both him and his girl in the “right” state.

ref_text: (Right, right, right)
tate_text:
This affirmative ending to the song is a sample of Q-Tip, a member of the rap group A Tribe Called Quest, from their 1993 hit track “Steve Biko (Stir It Up)”. This exclamation begins at the 1 minute and 25 second mark.

It’s interesting to note that this sample was edited with a slowed down tempo and almost phonetically sounds like “Roc” to symbolize Roc nation but in fact is not.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZItLBiHG9gc&feature=youtu.be&t=1m25s

These simple words spoken at the end tie the piece up nicely together as it serves as an agreement to the message Nicki Minaj and Beyoncé delivered for the past 3 minutes and 55 seconds.

The original song mentions things such as “beating your competition” and being the best lyricist:

Try to be the phattest is the level that we strive. Try to be the phattest also to stay alive

It is also important to note that Steve Biko was a strong political force for the ideology of “Black Consciousness” and this could be very pertinent considering the success of these two black females; an empowering finish indeed.

tate_text:
On “Not Afraid,” an inspirational track from Recovery, Eminem made a clear promise that he was done with feuds:

no more beef lingers
No more drama from now on

He realizes now he is breaking that promise, since “Fall” is a diss track aimed at many rappers (including Joe Budden, a fellow artist signed to Shady Records). Eminem is about to bring drama again, despite being sober or Paul and Dre’s advice.
