“These the motherfuckers” refers to some of the other artists out that can’t compete with Abel. These artists could even be people record labels coerce into recording music that sounds like The Weeknd’s in order to appropriate his sound. It’s a complaint, however, citing that their style and music doesn’t even come close to his. They’re always a step behind while Abel continues to evolve.

Initially House of Balloons, Thursday and Echoes Of Silence were all free mixtapes he released in 2011

They were later repackaged as “Trilogy” and sold worldwide in music stores





When Abel & Doc were making these 3 classic mixtapes they probably never thought that they’d be re-released in stores, yet alone go Platinum!

 Like an evil spell, I'm E-V-I-L (Evil, spelled)
tate_text:
Before modern medicine, physicians would hold mirrors to the human mouth and look for fog to determine if a person was still breathing.



The “Evil, spelled” adlib was added in post-production as a subtle jab towards critics who failed to notice some of the complex rhyme schemes from his 2017 album, Revival. Eminem addresses critics directly later in this track. The adlib itself rhymes with “evil spell” and notes that he spelt out evil – E-V-I-L.

Earlier on this track, Em spoon fed listeners a pun in a similar fashion:

Maybe “Stan” just isn’t your cup of tea (get it)

tate_text:
Some of Cole’s highest moments are the one’s that bring him to tears. From songs like “Lost Ones” and “Can I Live” to “Breakdown”, these songs are the most relatable for fans and they bring Cole to his higher self. Even in songs like “Be Free” which Cole says put him in a state of tears.

Moments like those, that bring fans together are what makes Cole “fiend,” or  crave to write. This satisfaction pushes him to hone his craft to give his fans the real connection they deserve. The word “fiend” may be a possible influence from Bas who often times says “everybody fiends.”

Important to note that he’s saying he doesn’t write down his lyrics. Not that he doesn’t come up with them himself. But why doesn’t he write? One could understand from these lines that it’s because writing is a non-revenue-generating waste of his time. He’s too busy a) making money, and b) shooting machine guns (commonly refered to as “choppers”).

These lines also contain a religious motif — tablet (10 commandments), sacrificing time to the “almighty” dollar, praising “almighty” power.

ref_text: Dutty wining 'round all these Jamaicans
tate_text:
“Dutty” means “dirty” in Jamaican patois.
Originating from Jamaica, “wine” is a form of dance, normally done by women, involving rotation of hips and waist. “Dutty Wine”, in particular, refers to a sexually explicit dance, including movement of legs in a butterfly motion and swinging of head. It is usually danced to the song  “Dutty Wine” by Tony Matterhorn.

ref_text: Last week was my rough week
tate_text:
He went through a lot last week, and had a very stressful one; which leads to the better annotated next line:



This is also a key change in his life, a con of fame if you will, as, in “Rescue You”, he says

You had a long day, I can tell by your face

and then, in “Enemy”, he says

Girl, I been drinkin' all day
Its been a long week,
Can’t you tell by my face?

“Enemy” was released after House Of Balloons, Thursday and Echoes Of Silence, and since he’s had to start making music for a living, this clearly shows that the effects of fame are rubbing off on him.

On another note,

When Abel sings “ Last week was my rough week” he is referring to taking a week of pills/opiates. When you stop taking opiates you always have one tough week of withdrawing and then things get better. You still experience some symptoms after the first week, hence the  next line “ I’m still drippin' down from my nose.”

ref_text:
Tiptoein' around my name, nigga, you lame
 And when I get at you, homie
 Don't you just tell me you was just playin'
 Oh, I was just playin', K-Dot
 C'mon, you know a nigga rock with you, bro
tate_text:
This could be a shot at Drake, who’s been involved in a subliminal war with Kendrick since 2013’s “Control.”

Kendrick mentioned Drake’s name on “Control,” but Drake has never put Kendrick’s name in a verse. However, he has subbed him on numerous occasions, including “The Language,” “Shit (Remix),” “6PM in New York,” “Used To,” “100,” and “Summer Sixteen.” The irony of these bars is the receiver is left unnamed, likely to leave the general public to decide.

In 2016, Drake tiptoed around Kendrick’s name again on “For Free:”

And like your boy from Compton said
You know this dick ain’t free!

Big Sean, another possible target of these lines who also has a history of possibly sending subliminal shots at Kendrick, might have tiptoed around Dot’s name in his 2016 song “No More Interviews.”

Sean mentioned “the savior of rap"—something Kendrick essentially refers to himself as on the same song.

These lines draw similarities to 21 Savage’s “No Heart.”

ref_text:
Now how the fuck did this metamorphosis happen?
 From standin' on corners and porches just rappin'
 To havin' a fortune, no more kissin' ass
tate_text:
In the early days, people would just rap for the love of rapping, not expecting anything to come of it. But once pioneers like Run-DMC, N.W.A., Dr. Dre, and Snoop Dogg started becoming rich and famous off of rapping, it started attracting people interested in making money that didn’t rap for the love of the game.

Eminem is also talking about his personal life here. When he was underground he would freestyle with his friends and battle rap strictly for enjoyment, but now that he is signed he is making millions off of an activity he used to do for free. This sudden change is hard to wrap his head around.

Noreaga had a similar line on Big Pun’s song “You Came Up”:

What what, we makin' it happen
From rappin' on the corners of blocks we going platinum"

ref_text: High like treble, pumping on the mids
tate_text:
Treble is a sound of high frequency. Bey uses a metaphor to compare her own high to the high frequency of treble.

Mids refers to mid-range sound frequencies—the beat keeps killing.

ref_text:
That white frost on that pound cake
 So your Duncan Hines is irrelevant, woo
tate_text:
http://players.brightcove.net/4863540648001/HklmClHkx_default/index.html?videoId=5237582444001

Yeah so the line ‘That white frost on that pound cake so your Duncan Hines is irrelevant’ – everybody considered that and took that as a drug line, when in all actuality it was just me talking about a description of the car.

Sometimes in my verses you can’t just take the line that you are questioning, you have to go to the line before or maybe a couple of lines before.

So it is really two-door preference, roof gone, George Jefferson, That white frost on that pound cake, which is the white paint job on the tan seat. And the Duncan Hines is irrelevant is because I used a cake reference and an icing reference, Duncan Hines was just the tie-in, essentially.

ref_text: You couldn't lift a single shingle on it
tate_text:
He’s suggesting that you couldn’t achieve what he’s already accomplished, much less raising his own kids better than he has, (in his opinion).

In the previous line, he said he’ll ‘raise the roof’. He’s continuing that metaphor, and saying you (other rappers) can’t lift a single shingle on it (reach my level of success). Also, shingles are usually put on roofs.

What artists often have to do is make generic singles to get attention, and with that attention they can then have more creative control over their music. Cole couldn’t just come in doing whatever he wanted, he had to be a bit more pragmatic in his approach

Gucc is a old nickname for Mark Pitts who is J.Cole’s manager also the President of ByStorm Ent. who founded BIG. One of his classic saying is play the game to change the game. Another one of his classic sayings is don’t change the direction, direct the change.

ref_text:
I promised Dave I'd never use the phrase "fuck nigga"
 He said, "Think about what you saying: "Fuck niggas"
tate_text:
There are a few Daves that Kendrick could be referring to here:



Dave Free (formerly known as DJ Dave), the host of some of Kendrick’s early mixtapes, president of TDE & Digi+Phonics producer
Dave from good kid, m.A.A.d city, who died in Kendrick’s arms after being shot by a rival gang member



While it could be any of these two, it’s most likely Dave from GKMC because his story fits the concept well. Dave’s death symbolizes the consequences of the things Kendrick is criticizing on this verse. Black-on-black violence, the inappropriate use of the N-word, and the phrase “fuck nigga” are things that Kendrick believes are only hurting the black community.

ref_text:
Do I do it for the love of the music or is there more to me?
 Do I want these niggas to worship me?
 False prophets
tate_text:
Following the previous lines regarding intentions, Cole takes a moment to reflect on his own. In Cole’s view, the love of music should be the main motivating factor for himself and his fellow rappers, as opposed to chasing success, riches, fame, or adulation. Those who do that and want others to worship them for it are false prophets.

While speaking with Microphone Check, Cole explained that although he has faith in the things that he speaks on, he doesn’t feel equipped to speak for others and be their “prophet.”

I’ve believed deeply in the things that I believe in and like, if you know me you know I’m passionate about these things I’m talking about everyday, but at the same time […] I don’t feel like the best candidate to be the voice of the generation.

Tyson’s biggest payday was an astounding $30 million in one night. He earned this twice – in 1997 for his fight against Evander Holyfield and 2002 against Lennox Lewis.



In the early stages of his career, Hova took advantage of Tyson’s fight to earn some extra cash:

I’m taking wages down in Vegas just in case Tyson / Have a major night off, that’s clean money

Now that he’s richer, he understands how Mike felt at the time.

ref_text: Down for the count
tate_text:
“Down for the count” is a boxing idiom. If a boxer gets knocked out the referee counts to ten and if the boxer can’t get up in that time s/he loses the match. So Eliza has definitely been “hit by the thunderbolt” here, and she’s not getting back up.

Counting is a major motif in “Hamilton” and several songs feature a count, including the next song (“Satisfied”) where Eliza’s sister counts to three, “Ten Duel Commandments,” “Take a Break,” “Blow Us All Away,” and of course “The World Was Wide Enough.” There is even a mini-count in this song–“one week later… two weeks later…” Hamilton is constantly counting down to the end of his life. Eliza endures this with him and continues to be a faithful steward of his memory after he dies. So Eliza really is down for the count! Everyone who gets married is.

“It’s all in me” directly references the act of penetration in the sexual context.

Interestingly, Ariana’s ex-boyfriend Mac Miller shared a similar sentiment with his album The Divine Feminine.

He told Pigeons and Planes:

The whole idea of the album was this belief in the whole universe being inside of a female, and that’s what I’m searching for so hard, to connect with the universe through love. It was too good to be true.

Ariana and Mac were frequent music collaborates, having worked together on songs like “My Favorite Part” and “The Way”, so it is possible that in some way the song’s theme was inspired by him.

 Yeah I feel you burning, everything's burning
 Don't fly so high

tate_text:
In the story of Daedalus and Icarus, the inventor Daedalus and his son Icarus were imprisoned by the King Minos. To escape, Daedalus created wings from wax and feathers.

He warned his son to not fly too high or too low, but Icarus became enraptured by the beauty of flight and flew too close to the sun, which melted his wings.



Vic uses this as a warning – if you become too caught up in something potentially harmful, it will come back to bite you.

This concept is likely a homage to Kanye’s short film, Runaway where the Phoenix (played by Selita Ebanks) burns up when she flies too close to the sun.

ref_text:
Cause all I see are wings, I can see your wings
 But I know what I am and the life I live, yeah, the life I live
 And even though I sin, maybe we are born to live
 But I know time will tell if we're meant for this
 Yeah, if we're meant for this
tate_text:
The biblical terms “sin” and “angel” represent the difference between Abel and the girls he preys on.

Similar to the line in his version of “Odd Look” in which he sings:

All you girls try to be saints, I’ll make you roll with a sinner.

Abel is a clear-cut sinner, his lifestyle consisting primarily of drugs and sex. This girl represents purity, being untouched by his “madness” initially. The two are polar opposites and will co-exsist regardless of how well they get along. This is truly the beauty behind the madness.

Abel has been this character since the beginning and he convinces ordinary girls to fall for him so he can can “live life for the moment.” This leads to a constant cycle of give and take, as these “angels” are willing to give Abel everything they can while he only takes from them. He wonders if the two can live this way, and if so, for how long.

This could also be interpreted as being about his rise to fame – he loves his old time fans, but now he’s hoping that he can truly “live” and come into his own in the mainstream. He hopes this transition will be successful, but only time will tell if someone like him is meant for this.

tate_text:
A drive-by shooting is a personal attack carried out by an individual or individuals from a moving vehicle. Drive-bys are a common form of gang violence.



Two of the most famous drive-by shootings were the murders of rappers Tupac and Biggie

ref_text: Feelin' like ET, flyin' out of the Addy
tate_text:
This is a reference to the popular 1982 film, E.T. The Extra Terrestrial which revolves around the protagonist, Elliot’s efforts to help a stranded alien, E.T., on Earth return back to his home planet. He has the powers of levitation which allows Elliot and a band of teenagers to escape law enforcement during a bike chase.

X claims he feels as if he’s flying, similar to E.T., when he’s taking Adderall, a drug that causes euphoria and enhances cognitive function.

ref_text:
And I try not to listen to nonsense
 But if you bitches are tryin' to strip me of my confidence
 Mission accomplished
tate_text:
In the past, Eminem was known for his explicit attacks against media and his critics. Most notably, on 2000’s “The Real Slim Shady,” he rapped:

Will Smith don’t gotta cuss in his raps to sell records
Well, I do, so fuck him and fuck you too!
You think I give a damn about a Grammy?
Half of you critics can’t even stomach me, let alone stand me

Among the controversial moments in his career, the worst case was when The Source exposed him for his racially-motivated bars  on “Foolish Pride,” a song that he wrote out of spite in his teenage years. Despite this, he pulled through and clapped back at The Source with “The Sauce.”

However, the tone of these lyrics is different from what Em has done in the past; he may have shown that he was aware of his decreasing popularity, but we’ve yet to see him truly succumb to his critics until now.

[MULLIGAN]
 Let’s have another round tonight
 
 [LAFAYETTE]
 Let’s have another round tonight
 
 [HAMILTON]
 Let’s have another round tonight
tate_text:
A bit of a compositional pun here, as the three repeat “let’s have another round tonight” one after another as if they were beginning to sing a musical round while in the process of getting another round of drinks. The joke is a little funnier if you know that rounds are mostly popular with the very young or the very drunk.

Oti, oti
 There's never much love when we go OT
 I pray to make it back in one piece
 I pray, I pray
tate_text:
In Yoruba (one of the Nigerian languages that Wizkid speaks), there’s some great wordplay going on that English listeners will miss.  See, “oti” means “no,” but “ọtí” (that’s oti with a short o and a rising i) means “liquor.”

Back in English, “OT” is an acronym for “overtime” or “out of town.” Drake has used it before, on ILoveMakonnen’s “Tuesday”:

Always workin' OT, overtime and outta town

Drake claims whenever he and his girl venture out of the city, they’re greeted with nothing but the threat of violence. He wants one more euphoric dance before they have to return to the dangerous streets.

ref_text: How could it be that the curtain is closin' on me?
tate_text:
In “Evil Deeds”, the first track of the previous album:

But the curtain just don’t close for me
This ain’t how fame is supposed to be

However, now the curtain truly is closing – but not the in the way Eminem had wanted it to. In “Evil Deeds”, he was talking the show being over, and how he should be able to go back to living a normal life. But the opposite happens here, where the curtain of his normal life is closing and he is now trapped as a performer.

Also some alliteration: could, curtain, closing.

Although it’s still early, Abel rhetorically asks when the night’s returning, as he can’t wait to hit downtown Toronto and pull key pieces for the party.

These lines give a nod to Public Enemy’s “Night of the Living Baseheads”, as there are different kinds of “baseheads” that could be found downtown:


Crack heads who are going to be up at night. After all, how can you sleep when you’re high on crack?

People who enjoy a lot of bass in their music (A.K.A. party animals/clubbers).



Abel can also pull attractive females while he’s downtown.

tate_text:
Abel knew he was destined to a life of mainstream success but he also cared about the people that listened to his music first: his original fans.

Due to the fact that he still was a local sensation by the time he dropped Thursday, he told his fans to enjoy the special time that they had with him at the beginning of his career before he became an international sensation and everybody loved his music.

People usually don’t like when an artist who they only knew and loved it’s now loved by everybody, it doesn’t feels the same to them anymore so they stop listening to their music and move on to another unknown artist.

In an April 2015 interview with MTV, Kendrick explained his release therapy is writing music. His life is music, and he sacrifices himself to get a message out.

Kendrick is dedicated to working on his music constantly, something he acknowledged in a February 2016 interview with the Recording Academy about his 11 nominations for the 58th Grammy Awards:

I knew I had to sit in the studio for a year or so process and just create, not letting no type of boundary stop me from doing what I’m doing. And that goes for the concepts. That goes for the writing process. That goes for throwing ideas on the wall [to] see if they stick, and different flows. Speaking on things that I feel like people don’t have voices can speak on.

I don't care about you, why you worried 'bout me?
 All I want is that smoke, give me all of that smoke
tate_text:
The Weeknd may be coming down or just gluttonously seeking some weed. His tone indicates an attempt at reassuring the audience that he’s not doing anything “serious,” and he further rejects concern by noting he doesn’t care about those who are worrying about him.

However, this dismissal is ironic considering there were 10 drugs referenced in this song – adderall,  alcohol/liquor,  cocaine, marijuana, XO – ecstasy and oxycontin, lean – codeine and promethazine, prescriptions and methamphetamines. Should we not be worried?



Originally, there was fan speculation that this lyric was directed at Drake (and possibly a response to this Drake line), as they were assumed to have fallen out when The Weeknd signed with Universal Records instead of Drake’s label, OVO. However, The Weeknd debunked the rumors that there was ever a beef between the Toronto natives in his Complex interview.

This sample comes from Amnesty’s 1973 track, “Liberty.”

The use of this sample was likely inspired by Kanye’s recent politically-charged tweets.

It could also allude to the concept of “lifting oneself up by the bootstraps”—a term prevalent in modern Republican rhetoric, as a counter to advocates of government welfare. The term has been heavily criticized in the political sphere due to its naive worldview. In addition, “Liberty” was featured on Amnesty’s 1973 album, Free Your Mind. This could tie in with Kanye’s support for “free thinkers.”

 I catch your eye then look away as if it never happened

tate_text: Love at first sight is an idiom. There are examples of this present in the bible, leading some to believe that love at first sight is a result of predestination or divine intervention. Western society idolizes this idea, since the majority of the population identify as followers of Christianity. Cole’s criticism can be seen as frustration with how people act when the topic is brought up, acting as if it’s “romantic”—even though he may be attracted to a girl at first sight, he knows it isn’t love.

ref_text: [Produced by Che Pope, Sham Joseph, Ben Bronfman, Noah Goldstein, Travis Scott, Mike Dean & Kanye West]
tate_text:
In 2012, Kanye West reached out to Ben Bronfman, looking for beats to use for his 2013 release, Yeezus. Bronfman got to work, creating this demo, titled “Cruel Cold Winter”.

https://soundcloud.com/blackdreamer-1/cruel-cold-winter

Although Ye only ended up using the intro (before any drums, vocals, etc come in), Bronfman was pleased with the final result, saying:

He almost accentuated the track more, the only part he took was the beginning part – he made it even more minimalistic.

It should be noted that the first time Bronfman heard any version of “New Slaves” was a month before the album release, on May 15th at the Adult Swim show at Roseland Ballroom.



You can read more about Bronfman’s role in “New Slaves” in this exclusive interview with Rolling Stone.

ref_text:
Alexander Hamilton
 My name is Alexander Hamilton
tate_text:
Our title character finally makes his grand entrance, with a distinctive establishing theme. Just in case you forget the name of our star or aren’t sufficiently ear-wormed by the melody, this motif reoccurs at numerous points throughout the show (spoken 6 times in this cadence by Hamilton himself, and another 9 times by the ensemble). Lin writes in Hamilton: The Revolution (p. 17) that the cadence came to him immediately and that Hamilton has “an absurdly musical name.”

This entrance is set up by introductions by Hamilton’s various contemporaries. Here’s Lin again, talking about this narrative choice (p. 16):

This [song] was originally written as a Burr monologue, when Hamilton was still a “concept album” in my head. It wasn’t until we realized we were writing a musical that we began to divvy up the monologue among the people who bore witness to Hamilton’s life. This owes a debt to the prologue of Sweeney Todd: All our characters set the stage for our main man’s entrance.

The sample used for this track is very similar to the one used on GZA’s intro to ProTools, unironically called “Intromental.”

The original sample for both tracks stems from the 1976 Soul Dog song, “Can’t Stop Loving You.” The producers mainly loop the first chords of the song, sprinkling in other aspects of the instrumental throughout.

Interestingly enough, Kanye had already sampled Soul Dog’s “Can’t Stop Loving You” fifteen years ago on The Madd Rapper’s “Not The One.” Looks like Ye owes Carl Mashall at least two songs!

The guitar solo was played by Kanye West’s right hand man, Mike Dean.

ref_text: Alexander Hamilton!
tate_text:
The first number sets a lot of precedent for the show, as mentioned in the summary. One of the more interesting elements is the way in which the show, particularly in “Alexander Hamilton,” is layered temporally; we’re in different tenses simultaneously in the show. It supports the sense of adventurousness, creative anachronism, and freedom that Lin-Manuel Miranda bakes into the voice of this work. It supports both the historiographical uncertainty and the playful multipresence that Burr & Hamilton (and the rest of the cast) will later explore (“The Room Where it Happens,” “The World was Wide Enough,” “Who Lives, Who Dies, Who Tells Your Story”).

We start with entirely past tense narration, giving the first decade and a half of Hamilton’s life via a chorus not really differentiated as characters yet, then we introduce Hamilton, and it’s his singular voice looking to the future—“just you wait.”

Once Hamilton has joined the conversation, the world has changed—neat categorization via tense and point of view gets more complex. Eliza hits two tenses in a single verse when she’s both recalling his childhood (past) and pointing us to the image of Hamilton in the sickbed with his mother (present).

We stick with straight past narration for a while until Burr (still not acting as Burr) puts him on the ship, again entreating the audience to see him in the present looking to the future. He tells Hamilton that in NY, he “can be a new man”—future, aspirational.

Then things get really wild. The chorus, in a delightful bit of meta drama, sings that they are “waiting in the wings for” Hamilton—speaking with expectation from the future to the past about farther into the future. They speculate about his legacy (a legacy they are in that instant touching, continuing meta riffs)—“when America sings for you, will they know what you overcame?”

Burr orients us again to Hamilton in the present aboard the ship heading for his (and our) future. He’s “comin' up from the bottom” as the company tells us “just you wait.” Then the players become characters, noting their relationship with Hamilton and summarizing their history (“I died for him,” “I’m the damned fool who shot him”). The company, though, continues to orient us to the future (of the show, and of the man), “just you wait.”

Burr brings us back to Hamilton in the present, asking him the fundamental question of identity—“what’s your name, man?”

The last line, then, is timeless. It’s identification. It’s aspirational and reflective, historical and personal. It’s pure, and it carries us into the more temporally-consistent (but definitely not locked), chronological body of the show.

That real life, real life, real life, real life

The two songs mirror each other; and, over the course of Beauty Behind the Madness, The Weeknd develops a connection between his emotional remoteness and  destructive behavior.

In Starboy, The Weeknd takes it a step further, thematically incorporating the effects of poisonous attention into his already addictive persona. The star of “Six Feet Under” is similarly attention-seeking, distant, hard working, and materially concerned. It’s in this bridge that he begins to explore the consequences of this deadly mixture: while she seems strong (“So she don’t waste her time /  So she don’t waste her time, oooh / You ain’t gon' catch her crying) the claim that she won’t "lose her mind” is almost completely undercut by it’s conclusion: an ominous “til she” which becomes “‘til she /six feet under.”

The message is clear: The Weeknd expects that for people like her and himself, such a life ends only in an early death.

Both X and Joey have gone through a lot of pain in their lives, which has made them become emotionally numb. Being numb is a form of passivity which makes people not feel emotion.

X’s main cause of this numbness has come from a rough childhood, heartbreak, and events leading to him being accused of aggravated battery of a pregnant victim, amongst other related charges. His debut album, 17, is largely based off these events.

One of the biggest factors emotionally impacting Joey would be the suicide of Pro Era member and best friend of Joey’s, Capital STEEZ, who jumped to his death from the roof of the Cinematic Music Group headquarters on December 23, 2012.

X was, as of release of this song, under house arrest and had been for several months. With all the hype that surrounded him at the time, he was likely very frustrated and so those months felt like years. In fact, he had been put on house arrest in December 2017, and had not been free for the majority of 2018 until his untimely death.

ref_text:
Wow, niggas been crampin' my style
 Blowin' my high, they want a reply
tate_text:
Cole expresses irritation over the presence of newer rappers, possibly “mumble rappers” or those that appear to be imitations of him, as he claims that they are “cramping his style”. He also mentions “blow my high”, a phrase that means ruining the high one receives from smoking marijuana, essentially fitting in with the drug-filled themes found in K.O.D.

It’s also worth noting that Cole may be giving a slight nod to frequent collaborator, Kendrick Lamar as he may be referencing his 2011 song, “Blow My High (Members Only)” which mentions various narcotics such as lean and as the title implies, marijuana.

Although flawless diamonds do exist, they’re exceedingly rare. Most diamonds have flaws or “inclusions.” Beyonce compares their love to a diamond—it has flaws but it’s still incredibly valuable, and its purity gives it strength.

One of Jay’s most famous symbols is the Dynasty sign, usually provoked by Jay saying “Throw them diamonds up.”



Although it’s incredibly hard to chip diamond, flawless or pure diamonds are considered the hardest natural material on Earth.

The same was used by Kanye West on his songs “Crack Music” and “Power.”

The jazzy outro was produced by Terrace Martin.

Instrumentalists for the outro include: Ronald Bruner, Jr. on the drums, Robert Glasper on the keys, Thundercat on bass guitar, Terrace Martin on alto saxophone, and Larrance Dopson with percussion. Background vocals were provided by Lalah Hathaway, who was sampled earlier on the album, on the song “Momma.”

The liner notes also credit production duo Katalyst with additional drum programming and engineering.

In a 2016 interview with Noisey, Boi-1da details how he came to work with Kendrick Lamar:

I’ve known Kendrick for a while pretty much before everything started happening with him. My good friend named Manny Smith that works at Interscope kind of put me on Kendrick before he really even transcended to where he is now. I’ve always had a cool relationship with him but Manny [Smith] just put us together. We just did a bunch of tracks, I was in with Kendrick for maybe a week and it was just really fun to work with him. He’s a great guy and he has a lot of energy in the studio. That was a joint that I had from before but I ended up playing it for him and he really liked that one. He said he had an idea for it so he did his thing on that one.

ref_text: [Produced by TNGHT, Kanye West, Mike Dean, Arca, Carlos "6 July" Broady, and 88 Keys]
tate_text:
The samples? The first one that starts playing at the very beginning of the song is Nina Simone’s rendition of Billie Holiday’s song, “Strange Fruit”. This sample has stirred up a lot of controversy, due to the extreme depictions of lynching in the sample. The meaning behind this sample is further elaborated on in this annotation.

This isn’t the first time Ye used this Nina Simone sample. In 2009, he used it for Common’s “Strange Fruit”, which some believe was intended for Com’s album Finding Forever. One theory is that the sample didn’t clear, which is why the track never appeared on the album.

The next sample comes from electronic duo TNGHT (Hudson Mohawke and Lunice) in the form of a trap banger, “R U Ready”. This track doesn’t sample anything, but it does interpolate the melody and drum pattern used in C-Murder’s classic, “Down 4 My Niggas”. This is more or less confirmed by Ye referring to “Down 4 My Niggas” in the bridge. In 2012, Kanye bought “R U Ready” from TNGHT, and even played it at his appearance at the Victoria Secret fashion show.

In the official Producer Genius SoundCloud breakdown below, you can first hear the “Strange Fruit” sample, chopped, leading into the beginning of Kanye’s track. Next plays a snippet from “R U Ready” to enable one to hear the comparisons, and finally, “Down 4 My Niggas” and Kanye’s respective portions are played.

ref_text: I almost cut a piece of myself for your life
tate_text:
Selena Gomez has consistently struggled with serious health issues due to her Lupus diagnosis.  The ordeal became worse during her relationship with The Weeknd, and she had to go through surgery in order to have a kidney transplant to circumvent eventual death from the disease.

In this case, the often metaphorical phrase “cut a piece of myself” could also be very literal; fans have theorized that Abel was possibly willing to donate one of his kidneys in order to save his girlfriend’s life.

Her best friend, Francia Raísa, ended up being her kidney donor, but Abel worked his tour around her surgery and cancelled one of his shows on his “Legend of The Fall” tour to be by Selena’s side during the ordeal.

ref_text: And pessimists never struck my nerve
tate_text:
This line is directed towards FOX News' commentator Geraldo Rivera, who criticized Kendrick’s BET performance of the 2015 song “Alright.” Geraldo claims that his lyrics are counterproductive, but Kendrick labels him a pessimist since he fails to see the positive aim of the song. In a 2015 interview with TMZ, Kendrick said:

How can you take a song that’s about hope and turn it into hatred? The overall message is ‘we’re gonna be alright.’ It’s not the message of ‘I wanna kill people.’

Kendrick also sampled the clip from Fox News in the songs,  “BLOOD.” and “YAH.”

This is a sample of Turkish singer Nükhet Duru’s song, “Ben Sana Vurgunum” (I Am in Love with You), where Duru sings a poem written by Turkish poet Sabahattin Ali. Translated to English, she says:

Each day goes on for years
I’m tired of going alone

The song was originally recorded in 1978. Listen here:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E0lI5169AYM

In an interview with Hurriyet Daily News, Duru said:

The Weeknd found me on my website and loved all of my songs. He found ‘Ben Sana Vurgunum’ appropriate since it has an erotic melody.

The sample provides a dichotomy: The Weeknd is singing how he is not alone and often having sex while Duru is singing about her loneliness. However, he might be doing this to deal with his own loneliness—he has no one to share his life with and it makes him empty inside, so he hides behind drugs and sex.

 That's like sayin' I'm the tallest midget (Ha-ya)

tate_text:
A “midget” is a term used for an extremely short person, often one afflicted with dwarfism. The tallest midget is therefore something a bit oxymoronic – “midgets” themselves are extremely short, so the tallest of midgets is still shorter than the average person. Out of all rappers, Jay’s labeling himself the best; it’s a bit of a weak label, though, because all rappers these days aren’t very good in the first place.

With the rise of a more “politically correct” culture, “midget” has been termed a hateful, insensitive term. Jay fits into a growing number of critics of “PC” culture, pushing concerns about sensitivity to the side after briefly acknowledgment.

This time, it feels more organic, as “Burr!” is used to catch his attention before leaving rather than as a greeting, as it does throughout many of the scenes before this.

 Note, though, that Burr responds to Hamilton with his FIRST name (“Alexander”), perhaps emphasizing the new power dynamic between them.  Generally, being called by your first name indicates you are in a lower position of power than being addressed by last name, almost like an adult to a child.  It can also indicate a highly familiar relationship, and one might say that now that Burr knows Hamilton’s' big secret, he has reached a new level of understanding Hamilton’s personality and motives.

In that regards, Burr is never referred to as Aaron by anyone – because no one really knows or is intimate with him.

ref_text:
When raindrops fell
 Down from the sky
 The day you left me
 An angel cried
 Oh, she cried, an angel cried
 She cried
tate_text:
Although this is a cover of the last verse of The Four Season’s “An Angel Cried,” these lyrics can be connected to the May 2017 bombing at Ariana’s Dangerous Woman Tour in Manchester, England. 22 concertgoers were killed, and several others were injured.

The attack is mentioned several times throughout the album, and “get well soon” even ends with a forty-second silence to honor the victims. This silence brings the track’s length to 5:22, to commemorate the bombing date, May 22nd.

A darkroom is a room with zero normal light present and is commonly used as a popular photographic technique. The intro to “Poetic Justice” may also serve as a representation of his teenage desires as shown on “The Art of Peer Pressure”.

We on the mission for bad bitches and trouble

Ultimately, one of the major thoughts that circle around K.Dot’s brain as a teenager is having intercourse with her as prominently expressed on the opening track of the album, mainly since he considers her to be a “hoodrat”.

“Casualty” can be defined as a person killed or injured in war—in this case, the causality is, you guessed it, your favorite rapper.

Kendrick follows up saying he assassinates his victims with stating that he does it casually—in a relaxing manner with no emotion. This connects to the “whistling to the melody” line in the first verse. Kendrick kills off rappers so often that it’s nonchalantly fun to him.

When he’s done, he collects his profit or “lump sum of hundred” dollar bills. This could be in reference to the profit he collects off of his album sales; Section.80 would eventually become RIAA certified gold, selling more than half a million copies.

ref_text: If young Metro don't trust you I'm gon' shoot you
tate_text:
Metro Boomin informs us of his involvement in this song with one of his many production tags; past ones include “Metro Boomin wants some more, nigga” and “Young Metro, Young Metro, Young Metro.”

The line itself comes from the bridge of Uncle Murda’s “Right Now” and is delivered by Future, Metro Boomin’s longtime collaborator. It gained prominence after appearing on Drake and Future’s hit collaboration  “Jumpman,” and even found itself in the political sphere, making its way into a Complex interview of former presidential candidate Ben Carson and protests of Donald Trump in Chicago.

In the weeks after this album’s release, use of this line in videos became viral, due to the infectious beat drop and jarring juxtaposition between “I’m gon' shoot you” and “Beautiful morning.”

Metro Boomin addressed the newfound popularity of his tag in an interview with Nardwuar the Human Serviette:

ref_text: We hung all summer, sprung mattress with bae bae
tate_text:
Kendrick is likely referencing Sherane, his teenage crush who he rapped about on 2012’s good kid, m.A.A.d. city. A “sprung mattress” is one with broken springs from too much sex. “sprung” is also slang for in love.

“Dyke” is lesser-known slang for Dihydrocodeine—semi-synthetic painkiller. “Trippin'” is slang for getting high.

Kendrick alludes to worker strikes, which are typically over wage amounts. Workers go on strike and don’t work in hopes of the company seeing how valuable they are.

ref_text: Trap drums is the shit that's hot now
tate_text:
This references the trap genre, a movement that became popularized during the 2000s and 2010s by Southern rappers such as T.I., Future, and Young Thug. It was characterized by its unique style of production which included heavy-hitting drums, hi-hats, and “booming” 808s.

Recently, the genre shifted its focus from lyrical content and instead, favored cadence and production. Cole, as a result, is frustrated that today’s generation would rather favor trap music over lyrical content, being a conscious rapper himself.

ref_text:
If I pull up with a Kerry Washington
 That's gon' be an enormous scandal
 I could have Naomi Campbell
 And still might want me a Stormy Daniels
tate_text:
In 2017, it was revealed that comedian Chris Rock—who announced the title for ye—was cheating on his wife Malaak Compton-Rock with several different women, including actress Kerry Washington who stars in the ABC TV show Scandal.

Kanye sympathizes with Chris’s motives, pointing out that power breeds temptation. Ye contrasts sophisticated supermodel Naomi Campbell with Stormy Daniels—an ex-porn star who caused an enormous scandal when it was revealed that President Trump allegedly had an affair with her while married to First Lady Melania Trump.

Moreover, the main plot line of Scandal involves Kerry Washington’s character (Olivia Pope) having an affair with the president. This links her to the line about Stormy Daniels and President Trump, who Kanye controversially supports.

It is also worth noting that Kanye likely chose to juxtapose Naomi Campbell and Stormy Daniels for another reason: the former is dark skinned, the latter is white. And as Kanye has mused previously, when a black man comes into money:

He’ll leave yo' ass for a white girl

ref_text: There are moments that the words don’t reach
tate_text:
Hamilton has always used his words to deal with situations. He writes himself out of his hometown destroyed by a hurricane and writes non-stop. But here Hamilton can’t use his words. The death of Philip is “unimaginable.”

Equally, he couldn’t use his words to break down the division between himself and Eliza—she knew his persuasiveness as well as anyone and had become understandably guarded and resentful of it after the Reynolds affair became public:

You and your words, obsessed with your legacy…
Your sentences border on senseless
And you are paranoid in every paragraph
How they perceive you

There was no persuading his way back into Eliza’s heart; only Philip’s death and her own grace could bring that about.

ref_text:
And it's one for the sheep who
 Led by your leopard, often gave his perception as a
 Handle of weapon,
tate_text:
The sheep is often referred to as an innocent, good-hearted animal in the Bible, as well as Christians following God like sheep.

X is talking about how a seemingly innocent sheep, symbolic of the average person, can be led astray into evil by a leopard, which could be representative of the more evil people in the world.

This is due to the things that an evil  life can offer in comparison to that of being morally strong are too tempting for the “sheep” to resist.
The leopard uses this fact to lure people into seeing things the way he does, hence his “perception” being his “handle of weapon”.

People know being evil may not be the right thing, but everyone has selfishness, one of the sins in Christianity, within them.

X may be saying he was once amongst the “sheep”, but a leopard, perhaps the devil he spoke to, led him to becoming evil and fulfilling his selfishness.

The leopard may also be a reference to Jeremiah 13:23. “Can the Ethiopian change his skin, or the leopard his spots?”. This may mean that he’s led by the tradition of people in bad positions doing bad things.

ref_text:
Burn
 Burn
tate_text:
During the song, Eliza uses the term “burn” to reference the rise and fall of her relationship with Hamilton, changing the meaning of the word throughout the song.

In this first part she claims the world seemed to burn, meaning that she was on fire with her passion for her future husband. She next refers to the tangible burning of the letters and his reputation in the eyes of the public. Lastly she says she hopes he burns, this time meaning his political career. It is also worth noting that Eliza was very religious and by the end of this song she is hoping Hamilton will burn and pay for his sins.

It is worth noting that Lin Manuel Miranda has largely credited Alan Menken’s Little Mermaid as a huge influence on his wanting to write musicals (first Ham4Ham y'all – http://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/16/hamilton-ham4ham-online-lin-manuel-miranda-alan-menken). The way this line is sung reminds me of the Part of Your World sung by Ariel in that film, where she says, “What’s a fire and why does it – what’s the word? Burn?” Same rising voice and emphasis. I would not be surprised if Miranda was aware of this and this similarity is on purpose.

ref_text: I’m in dire need of assistance…
tate_text:
On July 25, 1776, while the British fleet was gathering in New York Harbor, Washington wrote to Congress explaining that he desperately needed more staff members:


Disagreeable as it is to me, and unpleasing as it may be to Congress to multiply Officers, I find myself under the unavoidable necessity of asking an Increase of my Aid de Camps—The augmentation of my Command—the Increase of my Correspondance—the Orders to give—the Instructions to draw, cut out more business than I am able to execute in time, with propriety. The business of so many different departments centering with me, & by me to be handed on to Congress for their information, added to the Intercourse I am obliged to keep up with the adjacent States and incidental occurrences, all of which requiring confidential (& not hack) writers to execute, renders it impossible in the present state of things for my family to discharge the several duties expected of me with that precission and dispatch that I could wish—what will it be then when we come into a more active Scene, and I am called upon from twenty different places perhaps at the same Instant?

Congress will do me the justice to believe, I hope, that it is not my Inclination or wish to run the Continent to any unnecessary expence. and those who better know me, will not suspect that shew, and parade can have any Influence on my Mind in this Instance. A Conviction of the necessity of it, for the regular discharge of the trust reposed in me is the Governing motive for the application, and as such is Submitted to Congress by, Sir Yr Most Obedt & Most Hble Servt Go: Washington


(annotated text  here)



 (Washington in 1776, painted by Charles Wilson Peale)

tate_text:
Abel’s attitude toward women has shifted in his music. Not that the subject matter’s been toned down, but the Trilogy mixtapes featured a slew of women, whereas with Kiss Land and onwards, his mythos has delved into songs about just one woman.

ref_text: Messy like Binky, bon appetite, okay?
tate_text:
“Binky” refers to a pacifier (or dummy in some variations of English), an item given to infants or babies to suck on, intended to stop them from crying. Because they spend so much time in babies' mouths, they often end up dirty (messy) from saliva.



X references “bon appétit,” a French phrase said to someone about to eat, essentially meaning something along the lines of “enjoy your meal.” Much like a binky would go into an infant’s mouth, food goes into the mouth as well.

tate_text:
Kendrick started writing this song in 2012, immediately after the murder of Trayvon Martin. This was confirmed in an interesting article by Rolling Stone:

About three years ago, Lamar was flipping through the channels on his tour bus when he saw on the news a report that a 16-year-old named Trayvon Martin had been shot to death in a Florida subdivision. “It just put a whole new anger inside me,” Lamar says. “It made me remember how I felt. Being harassed, my partners being killed.” He grabbed a pen and started writing, and within an hour, he had rough verses for a new song, “The Blacker the Berry”:

“Coming from the bottom of mankind

My hair is nappy, my dick is big

My nose is round and wide

You hate me, don’t you?

You hate my people

Your plan is to terminate my culture. . . .“

ref_text: Feelings I harbor? All this pent-up resentment I hold on to?
tate_text:
Matthew has a lot of reasons to hate Em (the original autograph snub, his role in Stan’s death), and that anger has just multiplied over the years. And carrying that much anger with you at all times is dangerous.

Notice the slight homophone with “pent” and “pen”. Matthew has been writing letters to Em out of anger while still holding some of it back.

“Harbor” may also foreshadow how he plans to kill him by dumping him in the ocean. Clever as ever

tate_text: “Knock, knock. Who’s there?” Paints a civilised image of how a normal greeting at someone’s door would go. Wayne isn’t here for formalities, he’s here to fight and prove he is better than you.

ref_text:
Niggas put three bullets in my car, one hit the gas tank
 Know I got a angel cause I'm supposed to have a halo
 Right now, my lifestyle destined for a federal facility
 For my ability to make them birds fly
tate_text:
Many of Cole’s friends are locked in a federal facility, their freedom stolen by an institution. Similarly, birds that are trapped in a cage are unable to fly and be free despite their desires. This is also a nod to his 2015 song “Caged Bird”:

Yeah, caged bird
Freedom’s just an illusion, that’s my conclusion
And if it ain’t, then how my niggas keep on losin' theirs?

From James' perspective, his ability to make “birds” fly, or kilos of cocaine be shipped, should’ve put him in prison.

ref_text:
All she want is some heel money
 All she need is some bill money
tate_text:
Pusha can fulfill his girl’s thirst for money for heels and money to pay the bills… but I ain’t sayin' she a gold digger.



This is a reference to a woman’s claim that she needs money to pay her legitimate expenses – her bills – when the money really goes towards superfluous purchases like expensive high heels. Pusha is wise to her game and knows that she is really asking to be spoiled.

This could also be a slur of “Hill money,” a reference to Hillman College from The Cosby Show. This would tie to “Bill money” later in the line as a reference to Bill Cosby. This may seem unlikely, but Kanye has referenced Hillman before.

ref_text:
Hi, my name is, what? My name is, who?
 My name is, chka-chka, Slim Shady
 Hi, my name is, huh? My name is, what?
 My name is, chka-chka, Slim Shady
tate_text:
Dre put on the Labi Siffre record, and I was just like “Hi! My name is!” That beat was talking to me. I was like, “Yo, this is it, this is my shot. If I don’t impress this guy, I’m going back home and I’m fucked.” I knew Dre wasn’t an easy person to please. I made sure that everything he had a beat for, I had a rhyme ready to go, or I came up with a rhyme on the spot.

“My Name Is” was the first thing that came out of my mouth that first day I was at Dre’s house. I don’t know if we released what I did the first day or if I re-did it, but it was basically the same. I didn’t understand punching, or believe in it. So I would just go from the top of the song all the way down. I was never flying in hooks. Everything was live, one take. If I got all the way to the fucking end, and messed up the last word, I’d be like “Run it back, let’s do it again.” I remember Dre was like “Yo, are you fucking crazy? Let’s just punch.” I didn’t like that concept because I wasn’t used to it. When we were recording here in Detroit, in the beginning, I was saving up my money to go in. We only had an hour, you know? I’m like “One take down, alright, let’s go to the next song. Fuck it.” That’s what I was used to.

ref_text:
They say true love's the greatest weapon
 To win the war caused by pain, pain
tate_text:
“Love is the greatest weapon” is a phrase steeped in Christian meaning, used regularly to describe how faith in the Lord can heal wounds and end wars. It’s a common phrase in music, notably used by Jay Z on his 2003 track “Beware The Boys (Remix)”:

But only love kills war when will they learn

This war Bey is fighting was caused by the pain of infidelity, of the lies she discovered, expressed throughout this record. Walking away from the relationship would not win the war, it’d dissolve it, leaving no winners, and all losers. Trusting in true love and her feelings is the only way through the pain, the only way for everyone to come out a winner.

You forfeit the place in our bed.

In this line, Eliza substitutes “Come back to bed” for the words “Stay alive” that we usually hear in this melody. Coming back to bed would mean staying alive, here.

tate_text:
To “lie through one’s teeth” is to offer a blatant lie. “Fillings” are used to treat dental cavities, but this word also sounds like “feelings.”

Though not as advanced, this dental wordplay is  similar to that in Eminem’s “Not Afraid”:

You said you was king, you lied through your teeth
For that, fuck your feelings

Incidentally, it was speculated that Eminem’s line was targeted at Wayne himself; however, this was never confirmed.

ref_text:
And you've been going hard, baby
 Now you rolling with some big boys, baby
 Got a lot you wanna show off, baby
 Close that door before you take your fucking clothes off, baby
tate_text:
The girl’s efforts from the first verse were not in vain. She’s recognized for going hard, but she’s still not done; the sex is to come next.

She’s been rolling with the crew, either referring to Abel’s friends or his drugs. Either way, they’re big, or nothing to take for granted. “Rolling” is used to describe the high of ecstasy/MDMA, which is what the “X” in Weeknd’s record label XO stands for.

Around this time, the group must arrive at the loft. Abel tells the girl to shut the door before stripping as this experience should be an XO exclusive, or just between him and her. He probably explicitly says this because his girl is so high, her inhibitions are vanishing and she’s sexually stimulated.

ref_text:
Guess I was just another pit stop
 'Til you made up your mind
 You just wasted my time
tate_text:
A pit stop refers to the pit where a racecar driver stops in the middle of a race to refuel and/or service the vehicle.



The Weeknd uses a pit stop as a metaphor to suggest that a girl whom he “put on top” had just used him for her own needs, almost in the same vein that a car refuels at a pit stop. He states that she had not actually been in love with him in the same way he had felt towards her.

This is most likely a reference to his relationship with fellow singer Selena Gomez. Selena and Abel broke up on October 30, 2017, after 10 months of dating; the very next day photos emerged of Selena reuniting with her former boyfriend Justin Bieber (whom she split in 2015). Hence, Abel would have been Selena’s metaphorical pit stop.

tate_text:
Much like how most of the universe is a mystery to NASA, Ari believes that if she spends some time away from her man, she can be a mystery to him.

Since its inception in 1968, NASA has only explored an infinitesimal portion of the universe. This is because electromagnetic radiation or light from faraway galaxies and supernovae has not yet reached Earth to allow NASA to use its tools to study it. NASA’s photographic evidence of the universe extends only 13.2 billion miles, as a result of the 1977 Voyager 1 mission.

Ari similarly compares herself to the universe on the pre-chorus of July 2018’s “God is a woman,”:

(Yeah) And he see the universe when I’m the company
It’s all in me

ref_text: [Produced by Rick Rubin]
tate_text:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FqNDYvsOZkc
This is Rick Rubin´s first hip hop production in many years. Rubin provided Jay-Z with a guitar riff and stripped-down beat that were once his trademarks. In creating the track Rubin used some classic 1980s samples – it contains three.

The drums are sampled from “Mountain” by Long Red.

Multiple elements from “The Big Beat” by Billy Squier.

And also “Get Me Back on Time, Engine #9” by Wilson Pickett.
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n7sfOlQbD28#t=13

These samples appeared often and early in the arc of hip hop production. The drums from “The Big Beat” were used famously by Run–D.M.C. on “Here We Go” in 1985 and by British rapper Dizzee Rascal a year prior to Jay-Z on his break-through hit “Fix Up, Look Sharp”. It was also featured on the popular Ultimate Breaks and Beats series.

The title and chorus are taken from Ice-T’s “99 Problems” from his 1993 album Home Invasion. The song featured Brother Marquis of 2 Live Crew. The original song was more profane and describes a wide range of sexual conquests.

ref_text:
Wrote some songs about Ricky
 Now I listen and laugh
tate_text:
Ariana and Ricky Alvarez first became involved in April 2014 after becoming a backup dancer for her.

They first kissed publicly in June 2015 during Ariana’s performance at 2015 PRIDE. They were also seen kissing again during Ariana’s infamous doughnut shop incident, where she licked a doughnut that she did not purchase—confirming their relationship. They broke up in July 2016.

Ariana’s December 2015 song, “True Love” and May 2016 track, “Moonlight” were written about Ricky. Fans have also speculated that the tracks, “Into You” and “Forever Boy”, are about him, since the tracks were released while they were dating.



The phrase “listen and laugh” could mean she’s reflecting on the good times or the bad times with him.

ref_text:
I can hold my liquor
 But this man can’t handle his weed
tate_text:
When Vernon says “this man can’t handle his weed”, “this man” that he is talking about is actually Chief Keef and his version of the hook. Vernon’s hook is blurry and distorted, so it is trying to represent the effects of alcohol. And Chief Keef’s hook is displaying the effects of weed, as you can actually hear Chief Keef inhaling and exhaling smoke right before he starts his hook. Since both versions come from Kanye’s point of view, this “argument” demonstrates his inner turmoil. There’s a side of Kanye that is over-the-top cocky, but also a “dark and lonely” side that makes him feel worthless.

These two hooks are Kanye’s version of a devil and an angel on his shoulders fighting for control, since the messages both contradict themselves. Vernon’s hook shows Kanye trying to convince himself that he is awesome, even though he knows deep down that he’s just a lonely loser. And Chief Keef’s hook is Kanye beating himself up, even though in this version he thinks that deep down he is awesome and god-like.

ref_text: I put down the cans and they ran amok
tate_text:
The word “cans” has two meanings here,



First up, Jay took off the headphones (cans). As he says this line, the music stops. Is Jay just taking us back to this “can drop”? If so, the line refers to Jay’s stint with retirement post-Black Album. In that case, “running amok” is a reference to the drop in quality in hip-hop after his “retirement.” If that’s the case, then he calls his headphones “cans” because he compares himself to Picasso, and paints comes in cans.



“Can” is also a slang term for gun, so Jay could be talking about putting down his guns, i.e. retiring from criminal activity. Once he was no longer a gangster, people attempted to exploit his weakness in music.

ref_text:
[BURR]
 Don’t let them know what you’re against or what you’re for
 
 [HAMILTON]
 You can’t be serious
 
 [BURR]
 You wanna get ahead?
 
 [HAMILTON]
 Yes
tate_text:
Unlike Burr, Hamilton’s life to this point had not lent itself to traditional notions of civility. In Hamilton’s world, you needed to speak up in order to be heard above the masses. In Burr’s world, the masses were watching and listening to every word you said. This line serves to highlight how far removed Hamilton is from the world of polite society, and how ignorant he is of its more subtle arts. Burr recognizes that Hamilton is ambitious and wants to climb that social ladder, so, as his social superior, he condescends to share his philosophy for success with Hamilton.

However, in large part due to that upbringing of Hamilton’s, the advice falls on deeply incredulous ears.

The difference in their messages is echoed in their voices: Burr, smoothly and subtly explaining high-class behavior, sings his lines in a perfect, pleasing melody, while Hamilton’s lines are toneless and plainspoken. This is quite a change from earlier in the song, when Hamilton was rapping and rhyming while Burr was speaking in short, clipped sentences.

Burr not voicing his principles will become a recurring theme and conflict in the show. It ends up being the motivating factor behind Hamilton’s endorsement of Jefferson in “The Election of 1800,” which in turn sets up their final confrontation.

Kick your shoes off, let your hair down
 (And go berserk) all night long
 Grow your beard out, just weird out
 (And go berserk) all night long
tate_text:
Eminem wants you to have fun all night, and party! He loves having a good time, getting weird, and growing facial hair, apparently. What he doesn’t like is shoes on his brand new carpet.

Seeing as Rick Rubin worked on this track, it’s funny how Em states “take your shoes off” and “grow your beard out.”
This also calls to mind lines off his song “Business”:

Can’t leave rap alone, the game needs me
‘til we grow beards, get weird and disappear
Into the mountains



“Growing the beard” is also a term used to mean “defining an identity” – so named after the TV show Star Trek: The Next Generation, in which as it started to find its identity, coincidentally one of the main characters, Commander Riker, grew a beard.

Kendrick references Abraham Lincoln’s Emancipation Proclamation – which freed enslaved blacks in Confederate states during the Civil War. Slavery was not constitutionally abolished until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in 1865. However, even after the Thirteenth, Fourteenth (natural-born US citizenship), and Fifteenth (Voting Rights) Amendments were ratified, the white South still used fear to oppress the black population. Black Codes, Jim Crow laws, the Ku Klux Klan’s extralegal violence, poll taxes, Plessy v. Ferguson, sharecropping, and many other obstacles prevented the black population from exercising their constitutional rights.

He describes the cycle where white America sees his people as a violent uncontrollable “nigga” and thus condemns them, through laws and law enforcement, to being stuck in this self-perpetuating loop.

ref_text:
You woulda lost it
 Thirteen bottles of Ace of Spade, what it did to Boston
tate_text:
JAY-Z compares his 13 solo albums (4:44 is his 13th record) to 13 bottles of Ace of Spades Champagne. He owns a stake in Armand de Brignac, the company who produces it.

“Spades” and “Boston” are also nods to the card game Spades. Making 13 “books” in Spades is considered running a Boston—JAY-Z has made 13 albums.

In June 2011, the Boston Bruins celebrated winning the Stanley Cup by purchasing a 30-liter bottle of Ace of Spades dubbed the “Midas” for $100,000.

 But this one gon' last
 'Cause her name is Ari
 And I'm so good with that (So good with that)
tate_text:
The “better discussions” are a reflection of Ariana’s increasingly positive mental state. On her August 2018 album, Sweetener, she confronts her emotions following the May 2017 bombing at her Manchester concert. In her July 2018 ELLE cover story, Ariana described how she felt:

There were a couple months straight where I felt so upside down.

Apple Music originally had the lyric “her name is Ari” transcribed as “her name is Aubrey,” which caused a bit of controversy with fans who wondered if Ariana had a new lover or if she was talking about Drake, whose given name is Aubrey Graham. Apple later apologized for the incident and Grande confirmed the lyric was "Ari,” as in herself, “Ariana.”

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1058717538505252865

In the official music video, the mix-up was joked about, which Troye Sivan said:

ref_text:
Haven't you heard? I'm as cold as the tip
 Tip of the iceberg that tipped the Titanic
 No tip-toein' around it, my shit is gigantic
 As big as the fuckin' Atlantic, I'm lit, bitch
tate_text:
The Titanic was the first working version of a modern cruise ship that tragically crashed into an iceberg and sank on April 15th, 1912.



Cole compares the cold, savage nature of his raps to that of the iceberg the ship crashed into. Continuing the ocean theme, he boasts that his reputation is bigger than the literal size of the entire Atlantic Ocean which is around 41.4 million square miles.

He also subtly uses “bitch!” ad-lib he jokingly proclaimed as his signature ad-lib in “Forbidden Fruit” from his 2013 sophomore album Born Sinner.

He also used a similar iceberg comparison in Born Sinner’s bonus track “Miss America”:

Cole World, this just the tip of the iceberg

ref_text: [Verse 3: Kendrick Lamar]
tate_text: Throughout this verse, the instrumentation intensifies, with string parts joining along until eventually they set the stage for God’s revelation, in a musical climax that perfectly matches the lyrical content and leads into the desolate nature of Ronald Isley’s outro, illustrating how Kendrick comes so close to heaven and loses it all over selfish preconceptions. This verse, in a way, is the climax of the album, where Kendrick reveals that his fame has not only troubled his self-esteem and his roots, but also, in a very deep way, he is spiritually corrupted. All of his issues peak at this point to develop the revelation.

ref_text:
I tell 'em this too often
 Know better than to bark up my tree
 Just for me to fall and leave
tate_text:
Ariana is using clever wordplay here. Trees have bark on them, but Ari is also warning the person not to bark up her tree-don’t pursue her in a romantic way just for her to fall and leave, like the leaves fall off the tree.

She doesn’t want to fall in love with someone just for her to leave. Ari has dated several people in the last few years-Big Sean, Ricky Alvarez, Mac Miller and Pete Davidson. Due to the demands of her on stage persona and lifestyle, Ariana requires certain characteristics in a lover that her past loves seem unable to reach. She doesn’t want to get attached only to be in an unfulfilled relationship.

ref_text:
Wouldn't you know
 We been hurt, been down before
 Nigga, when our pride was low
 Lookin' at the world like, "Where do we go?"
tate_text:
“Wouldn’t you know” is an English idiom used as a preface to express dismay at one’s situation. Lamar uses the idiom to introduce the material, emotional, and psychological consequences of being Black in America.

“Lookin' at the world like where do we go?” is an authentic question of action that is the primary referent underlying all studies of the African Diaspora.

Lamar suggests that identity conflicts and a lack of pride are often corresponding conditions. He draws a connection between the positive development of Black pride/power and the potential personal/social/political revolution that can arise from struggling.

This leads into the next lines about police hostility towards Black people and potential retributive violence (“my gun might blow.”)

ref_text: Murder 'em, never heard of 'em
tate_text:
Quite deep from X here, he may be claiming one of two things.


The most likely explanation is that when someone kills another person, they deny any involvement or even knowledge of the person they’ve killed. This happens during many police investigations where convicted murderers deny the very existence and knowledge of the person they’ve killed.
He may be talking about the feeling of futility of Blacks in America, the sad reality is that homicides and black on black crime are hugely prevalent, a lot of gangsters for example involved in such violence leave their families and others may not have had much of a family to begin with due to estranged parents. If they’re murdered, who will be at their funeral, who’ll be there to mourn?

I was working with the producer Stephan Moccio and he did “Earned It” and a lot of other songs with Abel, one of which was “Angel.” I was set up to work with him and we had a really great connection, he’s doing most of my new EP coming out in February and we were just spending a lot of time in the studio at the point when they were finishing up and mastering “Beauty Behind the Madness.”

One night we were in the studio super late and we got a crazy idea, we were just like, “okay what if we just tried to sing on “Angel” and see how Abel would feel about it, just lay something down and see what happens. He could either hate it or he could love it.” And a few weeks later I got the call saying that he loved it.

ref_text: The Reynolds Pamphlet
tate_text:
The harp’s introduction to Burn can be heard here. For the theory people:

The harp accompaniment heard in “Burn” is in B-minor, where the background of “The Reynolds Pamphlet” is in C-minor. These two keys are not related, and they clash even more because B and C are just a half step apart. But through the orchestration of Music Director Alex Lacamoire, these tunes mix into each other and create a smooth transition to “Burn.”

 Girl, you're makin' it hard for me
 Girl, you're makin' it hard for me
tate_text:
These lines sung on the bridge by PnB Rock could have a triple entendre:


He could be referring to the problems he keeps facing in his relationship with this girl, all because she is making everything more difficult for them.
PnB could also be talking about not being able to resist this girl, even if he actually doesn’t want to develop something with her.
Or maybe, he could simply be referring to her ability to make him “hard.”



Although he wasn’t originally credited on the song, PnB Rock confirmed he sung this bridge on Instagram, which marks his first collaboration with X.



In April of 2017, it was rumored that PnB was going to be featured in a longer version of “I Don’t Wanna do this Anymore.”

Even though PnB’s only credit on this song is under “composer” and songwriter on iTunes, he has said to be collaborating with X on many other songs and considered him a close friend.

ref_text: I wrote financial systems into existence
tate_text:
This refers to Hamilton’s initiatives as Treasury Secretary which included establishing the national debt, forming a national bank, and using paper money rather than coin. Bringing something “into existence” also adds to the godlike diction associated with Hamilton in this verse. It’s not quite “let there be light,” but “let there be credit” did do quite a lot for America in the long run.

ref_text: I see death around the corner
tate_text:
Lil Wayne uses this line to reference 2Pac’s song “Death Around The Corner” from his 1995 album, Me Against The World.

The term is repeated throughout the song and describes how 2Pac felt his life would end up (as the song was written during one of the darkest periods in his life), ultimately predicting his death which tragically happened the following year.

I see death around the corner

Both XXXTentacion and Tupac’s murders were similar in the eyes of fans and hip-hop commentators, with both being shot in their prime and in their cars. It could also be possible that Wayne is using this line and link to 2Pac’s to show how X also had a feeling his death was “around the corner.”

tate_text:
Slim makes his entrance introducing the content of his ass : a crab, a “pesky pubic lice, that require treatment to remove, or they replicate and take over your entire crotch area” – U.D.



He then continues with the crustacean theme (lobster/crab), which is a reminiscent of his bar during the Redman collab' ; “With a hair up his ass like a rabbit crawled in his pants”. The next bar is also inspired from “Off the wall”.

For the “two rabbits” wordplay to be as he intended it, we would have to ignore the fact that technically, rabbits and hares aren’t the same thing.



Thus, let’s make an inventory of the things up his ass :


The metaphorical crab, sexual disease.
The rabbits/hares/hairs, rabbits being a notorious species of high reproduction capacity. “You two always be humpin' like rabbits !”
A koala bear, happens to be a ball of fur/hair, and also a “sexual position in which the male is on his hands and knees and the female is latched to his underbelly with her arms and legs wrapped around the male.” – U.D.
A ball of hair, a random third item up his ass to complete the theme.



All this to set up an animalistic sexual theme.

You can depict a story where Slim humps a chick in the koala bear position, gets crabs from it, and is left with pubic hair problems ; Slim is indeed back with a reminiscent of the Slim Shady LP:

ref_text: Woah, suddenly, I feel like takin' a PJ
tate_text:
Being aware of the large amount of money he has accumulated, Cole thinks about showing it off and spending it on vacation trips.

“PJ” stands for private jet, “D.R.” stands for the Dominican Republic, a sunny vacation spot in the Caribbean. Cole uses the two abbreviations deliberately to create some form of parallelism (“mili'”, short for million, would be another one). Also, “PJ” establishes the main rhyme pattern of the first half of the verse.

Now flying on vacation on a weekday further shows that Cole lives a lifestyle in which his leisure time isn’t limited to the weekend—he can go away whenever he wants. Eating good should also be part of a proper vacation, and ceviche is a seafood dish which is particularly popular in the Caribbean.

 They don't, they don't know

tate_text:
Chance could be alluding to Luke 23:34:

Then said Jesus, ‘Father, forgive them; for they know not what they do.’

Luke describes Roman soldiers who beat and mocked Jesus. Chance will protect the ones he loves from persecution.

Kanye also quoted Luke’s Gospel on “Why I Love You”:

Please Lord (forgive him) for these niggas (not know) what they do, ooh

On March 30, 2016, the line “No one can judge” was incorporated as part of an across-the-board update of The Life of Pablo.

ref_text:
Raise a glass to freedom
 Something they can never take away
tate_text:
Many of the Founding Fathers were obsessed with legacies, success or other measurable things. Laurens advocated for the end of slavery; Hamilton wanted to be remembered; Lafayette and Mulligan were both determined to free America from British rule.
None of these goals were guaranteed; they all involved taking risks with the hopes of succeeding. However, freedom is something that, in the minds of these men, they are fighting for something that is undeniable. Freedom is so entirely fundamental, that even if they do not have their other dreams, freedom is something that they can rely on so when they raise their glasses to freedom, they are raising their glasses to their only guarantee. These men don’t know if they will live or die; they don’t know if they’ll be remembered or just be another name in history. All that they do know is that they are free and that they will die free. This is something that they fall back on; with everything else unknown and doubtable, they need some sort of guarantee to keep themselves safe and their freedom is this guarantee.

ref_text:
I'll be different, oh
 I think I'll be different, ooh
 I hope I'm not different, oh
 And I hope you'll still listen
tate_text:
The word, “different” has a variety of interpretations in this part. Abel wants to be different as compared to other guys she’s seen before and different in the eyes of his fans who haven’t heard this type of music. He attempts to convince himself that he will be different towards them while also hoping that he’s not different in which he doesn’t want to stand out too much.

Abel, in regards to signing with Republic Records, explained on an open letter he published along the “Rolling Stone” music video:

I want you to know and understand that this does not mean what you think it means, and I made sure of that in my deal. You will continue to get what you fell in love with, and I will continue to give you what you ask for.

It’s very clear that he didn’t want to go mainstream but in his own words: “it is a step that I feel I must take to evolve as an artist.” Every amazing artist in history knew that in order to keep being relevant they had to evolve and experiment with their music—just ask Kanye. But what’s most important is that he also wanted to keep making the music that he and his original fans fell in love with.

ref_text: I love my sister more than anything in this life
tate_text:
A bit of music theory terminology:  to modulate is to change the key of a song. In this stanza, Angelica reprises a melody from “Satisfied” in the original key.  Then, as her sentiment toughens, she modulates in line 3. You can hear she’s singing the same general melodic shape, but in lines 3 & 4, the pitches are higher than they were in lines 1 & 2.  You’ll also note that the interval is bigger after she modulates (from minor third to perfect fourth).



Additionally, Angelica doesn’t let Hamilton voice his opinion here: whatever he could say in his own defense doesn’t matter. She makes her decision about whose side she’s on without getting any input from the (sometimes) love of her life.

In short, Angelica has modulated the key without debating with Hamilton.  Way to use his own idea against him, Angie.
